# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: baltimore-clipper
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] The **Act Prohibiting Importation of Slaves** of 1807 (2 Stat.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] 426, enacted March 2, 1807) is a United States federal law that prohibits the importation of slaves into the United States.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] It took effect on January 1, 1808, the earliest date permitted by the United States Constitution.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] This legislation was promoted by President Thomas Jefferson, who called for its enactment in his 1806 State of the Union address.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] He and others had promoted the idea since the 1770s.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] It reflected the general trend toward abolishing the international slave trade, which Virginia, followed by all the other states, had prohibited or restricted since then (South Carolina, however, had reopened its trade).
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Congress first regulated against the trade in the Slave Trade Act of 1794, which made it illegal for American ships to participate in the trade.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] The 1807 law took matters further by criminalizing all importation from abroad, even on foreign ships.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] The domestic slave trade within the United States was not affected by the 1807 law.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Indeed, with the legal supply of imported slaves terminated, the domestic trade increased in importance.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] In addition, some smuggling of slaves persisted.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] The Act affected only the import or export of slaves, and did not affect the internal trade in states or between states.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Georgia received transatlantic slave ships until 1798.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] South Carolina reopened the transatlantic slave trade in December 1803 and imported 39,075 enslaved people of African descent between 1804 and 1808).
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Article 1 Section 9 of the United States Constitution protected a state's involvement in the Atlantic slave trade for twenty years from federal prohibition.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Article 5 said that this clause could not be affected by constitutional amendment.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Only starting on January 1, 1808, could there be a federal law to abolish the international slave trade in all states, although individual states could and did ban it before such time.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] By 1775, Africans both free and enslaved made up 20% of the population in the Thirteen Colonies, which made them the second-largest ethnic group after English Americans.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] In 1774, the influential, revolutionary Fairfax Resolves, called for an end to the "wicked, cruel, and unnatural" Atlantic slave trade.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] During the Revolutionary War, the United Colonies all pledged to ban their involvement in the transatlantic slave trade.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] This was done for a variety of economic, political, and moral reasons depending on the colony.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] By 1807, only South Carolina allowed the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] On March 22, 1794, Congress passed the Slave Trade Act of 1794, which prohibited making, loading, outfitting, equipping or dispatching of any ship to be used in the trade of slaves, essentially limiting the trade to foreign ships.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] On August 5, 1797, John Brown of Providence, Rhode Island became the first American to be tried in federal court under the 1794 law.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Brown was convicted and was forced to forfeit his ship *Hope*.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] However, the same act also abolished the importation of slaves to the Mississippi Territory from "foreign parts" (foreign nations).
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] The penalty for illegally importing slaves from abroad to the territory was a fine of $300.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] In the Slave Trade Act of 1800, Congress outlawed U.S. citizens' investment in the trade and the employment of U.S. citizens on ships involved in the trade.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] On March 3, 1805, Joseph Bradley Varnum submitted a Massachusetts Proposition to amend the Constitution and Abolish the Slave Trade.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Under Varnum's leadership, legislation moved through Congress and passed both houses on March 2, 1807.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] President Thomas Jefferson signed the bill into law on March 2, 1807.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Many in Congress believed the act would doom slavery in the South, but they were mistaken.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] The role of the Navy was expanded to include patrols off the coasts of Cuba and South America.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] The effective date of the Act, January 1, 1808, was celebrated by Peter Williams, Jr., in "An Oration on the Abolition of the Slave Trade" delivered in New York City.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] While there are no exact figures known, historians estimate that up to 50,000 slaves were illegally imported into the United States after 1808, mostly through Spanish Florida and Texas, before those states were admitted to the Union.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] However, South Carolina Governor Henry Middleton estimated in 1819 that 13,000 smuggled African slaves arrived every year.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] In 1820, slave trading became a capital offense with an amendment to the 1819 Act to Protect the Commerce of the United States and Punish the Crime of Piracy.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] A total of 74 cases of slaving were brought in the United States between 1837 and 1860, "but few captains had been convicted, and those had received trifling sentences, which they had usually been able to avoid".
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Nathaniel Gordon, who was hanged in 1862, was the only person to be executed for illegal slave-trading in the United States.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] In addition, after the 1808 abolition of the slave trade to the United States, many Americans continued to engage in the slave trade by transporting Africans to Cuba.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] From 1808 to 1860, almost one-third of all slave ships either were owned by American merchants or were built and outfitted in American ports.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] It is possible that U.S. citizens "may have transported twice as many Africans to other countries such as Cuba and Brazil as they did to their own ports".
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Navy was slow to institute anti-slaving patrols off the slave ports of Africa—it was not until the 1820 legislation that authority was given to the president to use naval vessels for this task.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Even then, enforcement activity was sporadic and largely ineffective.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] The U.S. position meant that many slave ships from other countries falsely flew the American flag to avoid being seized by British anti-slaving patrols.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] The first U.S. warship sent to the African coast to intercept U.S. vessels operating in the illegal trade was the USS *Cyane*.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Navy ships were on station there in 1820 and 1821, arresting 11 American slavers.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] No further U.S. anti-slaving patrols were carried out until 1842, and then with limited effectiveness due to political pressure from the slave-owning states.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] The Atlantic slave trade was not ended until the U.S.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Civil War, when American-built and -managed ships were prevented from operating.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] In the South, the Fire-Eaters—antebellum pro-slavery extremists—proposed repealing the act and once more legalizing the international slave trade in the United States.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Historian Erskine Clarke writes that this call "was a shameless expression of their contempt for any antislavery sentiment and a part of their stratagem to divide the nation and create a slaveholding confederacy.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] The view alarmed even pro-slavery figures, such as former President John Tyler, who in retirement wrote a widely republished letter condemning the Fire-Eaters' call to abrogate Article 8 of the Webster–Ashburton Treaty (which barred the slave trade).
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Tyler noted that the South had voted to ratify the treaty.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Slavery and the cotton economy boomed during the 1850s, and cotton prices were resurgent after a decline in the 1840s.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] This, in turn, drove up the price of slaves, which led to further pressure to re-open the slave trade to meet demand or bring down prices.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Not all Southerners felt this way, however, as the high price of slaves benefitted slave owners and slave merchants.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] But the general sentiment called for a re-opening of the trade as a logical extension of the support for slavery.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Southerners reasoned that, if slavery was good, then putting more people into slavery must also be good, and that, if trading slaves in the South was okay, then trading them from Africa must also be okay.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Conventions of Southern planters repeatedly called for the trade to re-open.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] This, of course, was a non-starter in Congress.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] There were also attempts from state legislatures to allow the importation of "apprentices" from Africa, but without success.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] When trying to repeal the slave act failed, some turned to simply ignoring it.
[src:baltimore-clipper/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Notable cases during the 1850s included slaves smuggled aboard the *Wanderer* and the *Clotilda*.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] 1620), also known as the **Age of Exploration**, was part of the early modern period and overlapped with the Age of Sail.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] It was a period from approximately the 15th to the 17th century, during which seafarers from European countries explored, colonized, and conquered regions across the globe.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The Age of Discovery was a transformative period when previously isolated parts of the world became connected to form the world-system, and laid the groundwork for globalization.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The extensive overseas exploration, particularly the opening of maritime routes to the East Indies and European colonization of the Americas by the Spaniards and Portuguese, later joined by the English, French, and Dutch, spurred international global trade.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The interconnected global economy of the 21st century has its origins in the expansion of trade networks during this era.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The exploration created European colonial empires and marked an increased adoption of colonialism as a government policy in several European states.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] As such, it is sometimes synonymous with the first wave of European colonization.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] This colonization reshaped power dynamics causing geopolitical shifts in Europe and creating new centers of power beyond Europe.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Portuguese oceanic exploration began with maritime expeditions to the Macaronesian islands, including the Canary Islands, as well as Madeira and the Azores.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] It continued with voyages along the coast of West Africa in 1434, and culminated in the establishment of a sea route to India in 1498 by Vasco da Gama, which initiated Portugal's maritime and commercial presence in Kerala and the Indian Ocean.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Spain also undertook other major early voyages, including the conquest of Mexico (1519–1521), the conquest of Peru (1532–1533), and the Manila galleon trade route (1565–1815), which linked the Americas and Asia across the Pacific.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] European exploration initiated the Columbian exchange between the Old World (Europe, Asia, and Africa) and New World (Americas).
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] This exchange involved the transfer of plants, animals, human populations (including slaves), communicable diseases, and culture across the Eastern and Western Hemispheres.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The Age of Discovery and European exploration involved mapping the world, shaping a new worldview and facilitating contact with distant civilizations.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The continents drawn by European mapmakers developed from abstract "blobs" into the outlines more recognizable to us.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Simultaneously, the spread of new diseases, especially affecting American Indians, led to rapid declines in some populations.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The era saw widespread enslavement, exploitation and military conquest of Indigenous peoples, concurrent with the growing economic influence and spread of Western culture, science, and technology leading to a faster-than-exponential population growth world-wide.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The concept of discovery has been scrutinized, critically highlighting the history of the core term of this periodization.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The term "age of discovery" is in historical literature and still commonly used.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Something of which they had no prior knowledge had suddenly presented itself to their gaze." O'Gorman argues that the physical encounter with new territories was less important than the Europeans' effort to integrate this new knowledge into their worldview, what he calls "the invention of America".
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Pagden examines the origins of the terms "discovery" and "invention".
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In English, "discovery" and its forms in romance languages derive from "*disco-operio*, meaning to uncover, to reveal, to expose to the gaze", what was revealed existed previously.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Few Europeans during the period used the term "invention" for the European encounters, with the exception of Martin Waldseemüller, whose map first used the term "America".
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] A central legal concept of the discovery doctrine, expounded by the United States Supreme Court in 1823, draws on assertions of European powers' right to claim land during their explorations.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The concept of "discovery" has been used to enforce colonial claiming and discovery, but has been challenged by Indigenous peoples and researchers.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Many indigenous peoples have fundamentally challenged the concept of colonial claiming of "discovery" over their lands and people, as forced and negating indigenous presence.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The period alternatively called the *Age of Exploration*, has been scrutinized through reflections on the exploration.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Its understanding and use, has been discussed as being framed and used for colonial ventures, discrimination and exploitation, by combining it with concepts such as the frontier (as in Frontier Thesis) and manifest destiny, up to the contemporary age of space exploration.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Alternatively, the term *contact*, as in first contact, has been used to shed more light on the age of discovery and colonialism, using the alternative names of *Age of Contact* or *Contact Period*, discussing it as an "unfinished, diverse project".
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The Portuguese began systematically exploring the Atlantic coast of Africa in 1418, under the sponsorship of Prince Henry the Navigator.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1488, Bartolomeu Dias reached the Indian Ocean by this route.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1492, the Catholic Monarchs of Spain funded Genoese mariner Christopher Columbus's (Italian: *Cristoforo Colombo*) plan to sail west to reach the Indies, by crossing the Atlantic.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus encountered a continent uncharted by Europeans (though it had been explored and temporarily colonized by the Norse 500 years earlier).
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Later, it was called America after Amerigo Vespucci, a trader working for Portugal.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal quickly claimed those lands under the terms of the Treaty of Alcáçovas, but Castile was able to persuade the Pope, who was Castilian, to issue four papal bulls to divide the world into two regions of exploration, where each kingdom had exclusive rights to claim newly discovered lands.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] These were modified by the Treaty of Tordesillas, ratified by Pope Julius II.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1498, a Portuguese expedition commanded by Vasco da Gama reached India by sailing around Africa, opening up direct trade with Asia.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The Portuguese sailed further eastward, to the valuable Spice Islands in 1512, landing in China one year later.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Japan was reached by the Portuguese in 1543.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1513, Spanish explorer Vasco Núñez de Balboa crossed the Isthmus of Panama and reached the "other sea" from the New World.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Thus, Europe first received news of the eastern and western Pacific within a one-year span around 1512.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] East and west exploration overlapped in 1522, when a Spanish expedition sailing westward, led by Portuguese navigator Ferdinand Magellan (and, after his death in what is now the Philippines, by navigator Juan Sebastián Elcano), completed the first circumnavigation of the world.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Spanish *conquistadors* explored the interior of the Americas, and some of the South Pacific islands.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Their main objective was to disrupt Portuguese trade in the East.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1495, the French, English, and Dutch entered the race of exploration, after learning of Columbus' exploits, defying the Iberian monopoly on maritime trade by searching for new routes.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The first expedition was led by John Cabot in 1497 to the north, in the service of England, followed by French expeditions to South America and later to North America.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Later expeditions went to the Pacific Ocean around South America, and eventually by following the Portuguese around Africa, into the Indian Ocean; discovering Australia in 1606, New Zealand in 1642, and Hawaii in 1778.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 1580s to the 1640s, Russians explored and conquered almost the whole of Siberia, and claimed Alaska in the 1730s.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] After the fall of the Western Roman Empire largely severed the connection between Europe and lands further east, Christian Europe was largely a backwater compared to the Muslim world, which conquered and incorporated large territories in the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The Christian Crusades to retake the Holy Land from the Muslims were not a military success, but they did bring Europe into contact with the Middle East and the valuable goods manufactured or traded there.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 12th century, the European economy was transformed by the interconnecting of river and sea trade routes.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Economic growth of Iberia followed the Christian reconquest of Al-Andalus in what is now southern Spain and the siege of Lisbon (1147 AD), in Portugal.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The decline of the Fatimid Caliphate's naval strength, which started before the First Crusade, helped the maritime Italian states, mainly Venice, Genoa and Pisa, dominate trade in the Eastern Mediterranean, with merchants there becoming wealthy and politically influential.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The Norman conquest of England, in the late 11th century, allowed for peaceful trade on the North Sea.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The Hanseatic League, a confederation of merchant guilds and their towns in north Germany, along the North Sea and Baltic Sea, was instrumental in the commercial development of the region.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In the 12th century, the regions of Flanders, Hainault, and Brabant produced the finest quality textiles in northwest Europe, which encouraged merchants from Genoa and Venice to sail there from the Mediterranean, through the Strait of Gibraltar, and up the Atlantic coast.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Nicolòzzo Spinola made the first recorded direct voyage from Genoa to Flanders in 1277.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Technological advancements that were important to the Age of Exploration were the adoption of the magnetic compass and advances in ship design.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass was an addition to the ancient method of navigation based on sightings of the sun and stars.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] It was invented during the Chinese Han dynasty and had been used for navigation in China by the 11th century.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] It was adopted by Arab traders in the Indian Ocean.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass spread to Europe by the late 12th or early 13th century.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Use of the compass for navigation in the Indian Ocean was first mentioned in 1232.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The first mention of use of the compass in Europe was in 1180.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The Europeans used a "dry" compass, with a needle on a pivot.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass card was also a European invention.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The ships of the Age of Discovery post-dated the fusion of the northern European and Mediterranean shipbuilding traditions.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Prior to the late 13th/early 14th centuries, northern European ships were typically clinker built, with a single mast setting a square sail and a centre-line rudder hung on the sternpost with pintles and gudgeons.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Their counterparts in the Mediterranean were built with carvel hulls, had one or more masts (depending on size) which set lateen sails, and were steered with quarter-rudders positioned on the side of the hull.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Trade, pilgrimage and war brought ships from each tradition into the other's region, ultimately leading to the copying of features that were new to each.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Over the early 14th century, square sails started to be used in the Mediterranean, with the mainmast setting square rig and the mizzen carrying a lateen sail.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In the first two decades of the 15th century this arrangement was copied in northern Europe where, by the late 1430s, some ships were built with carvel hulls.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The result of this merging of traditions was the full-rigged ship, a carvel hull with a sternpost-hung pintle-and-gudgeon rudder and three masts: the foremast and mainmast setting square sails and the mizzen a lateen sail.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Alongside this type of vessel, the caravel was used.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] This type was also carvel built with a sternpost-hung rudder but could be completely lateen rigged or have some square sails.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Very few wrecks of Age of Discovery ships have been found and archaeologically investigated.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] More is known about Roman and Greek ships of classical antiquity than those of this period.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The caravel is particularly poorly understood, despite the number of "replicas" that have been constructed.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] However, a particular set of hull construction characteristics have been identified from wrecks of this time, referred to as Iberian Atlantic shipbuilding tradition.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] They are found in the Molasses Reef wreck, Highbourne Cay wreck, the Red Bay wreck and some sites in European waters.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] European medieval knowledge about Asia beyond the reach of the Byzantine Empire was sourced in partial reports, often obscured by legends, dating back from the conquests of Alexander the Great and successors.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Another source was the Radhanite Jewish trade networks of merchants established as go-betweens between Europe and the Muslim world during the time of the Crusader states.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] There were reports of great African Sahara, but the knowledge was limited for the Europeans, to the Mediterranean coast and little else, since the Arab blockade of North Africa precluded exploration inland.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Knowledge about the Atlantic African coast was fragmented and derived mainly from old Greek and Roman maps based on Carthaginian knowledge, including Roman exploration of Mauritania.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The Red Sea was barely known and only trade links with the maritime republics, Venice especially, fostered the collection of accurate maritime knowledge.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Indian Ocean trade routes were sailed by Arab traders.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] By 1400, a Latin translation of Ptolemy's *Geographia* reached Italy from Constantinople.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The rediscovery of Roman geographical knowledge was a revelation, both for map-making and worldview, although reinforcing the idea that the Indian Ocean was landlocked.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] A prelude to the Age of Discovery was a series of European expeditions crossing Eurasia by land in the late Middle Ages.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The Mongols had threatened Europe, but Mongol states also unified much of Eurasia and, from 1206 on, the *Pax Mongolica* allowed safe trade routes and communication lines from the Middle East to China.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The close Italian links to the Levant raised curiosity and commercial interest in countries which lay further east.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] There are a few accounts of merchants from North Africa and the Mediterranean, who traded in the Indian Ocean in late medieval times (see also Indo-Mediterranean § Medieval era).
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Christian embassies were sent as far as Karakorum during the Mongol invasions of the Levant, from which they gained a greater understanding of the world.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The first of these travellers was Giovanni da Pian del Carpine, dispatched by Pope Innocent IV to the Great Khan, who journeyed to Mongolia and back from 1241 to 1247.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Russian prince Yaroslav of Vladimir, and his sons Alexander Nevsky and Andrey II of Vladimir, travelled to the Mongolian capital.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Though having strong political implications, their journeys left no detailed accounts.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Other travellers followed, like French André de Longjumeau and Flemish William of Rubruck, who reached China through Central Asia.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Marco Polo, a Venetian merchant, dictated an account of journeys throughout Asia from 1271 to 1295, describing being a guest at the Yuan dynasty court of Kublai Khan in *Travels*.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The Muslim fleet guarding the Strait of Gibraltar was defeated by Genoa in 1291.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In that year, the Genoese attempted their first Atlantic exploration when merchant brothers Vadino and Ugolino Vivaldi sailed from Genoa with two galleys, but disappeared off the Moroccan coast, feeding fears of oceanic travel.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1325 to 1354, a Moroccan scholar from Tangier, Ibn Battuta, journeyed through North Africa, the Sahara desert, West Africa, Southern Europe, Eastern Europe, the Horn of Africa, the Middle East, and Asia, having reached China.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] After returning, he dictated an account to a scholar he met in Granada, *The Rihla* ("The Journey"), the unheralded source on his adventures.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1357 and 1371, a book of supposed travels compiled by John Mandeville acquired popularity.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Despite the unreliable and often fantastical nature of its accounts, it was used as a reference for the East, Egypt, and the Levant in general, asserting the old belief that Jerusalem was the centre of the world.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Following the period of Timurid relations with Europe, in 1439, Niccolò de' Conti published an account of his travels as a Muslim merchant to India and Southeast Asia.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1466–1472, Russian merchant Afanasy Nikitin of Tver travelled to India, which he described in his book *A Journey Beyond the Three Seas*.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] These overland journeys had little immediate effect.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The Mongol Empire collapsed almost as quickly as it formed and soon the route to the east became more difficult and dangerous.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The Black Death of the 14th century also blocked travel and trade for a time.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Religion played a critical role in motivating European expansionism.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1487, Portuguese envoys Pero da Covilhã and Afonso de Paiva were sent on a covert mission to gather intelligence on a potential sea route to India and inquire about Prester John, a Nestorian patriarch and king, believed to rule over parts of the subcontinent.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Covilhã was warmly received upon his arrival in Ethiopia, but forbidden from leaving.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] During the Middle Ages, the spread of Christianity throughout Europe fueled the desire to sermonise in lands beyond.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] This evangelical effort became a significant part of the military conquests of European powers, like Portugal, Spain, and France, often leading to the conversion of indigenous peoples, voluntarily or forced.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Religious orders such as the Franciscans, Dominicans, Augustinians, and Jesuits partook in most missionary endeavours in the New World.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] By the late 16th and 17th centuries, the latter's presence increased as they sought to reassert their power and revive the Catholic culture of Europe, which had been damaged by the Reformation.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The Chinese had wide connections through trade in Asia and been sailing to Arabia, East Africa, and Egypt since the Tang dynasty (AD 618–907).
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1405 and 1421, the third Ming emperor Yongle sponsored long range tributary missions in the Indian Ocean under the command of admiral Zheng He.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] A large fleet of new junk ships was prepared for the international diplomatic expeditions.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The largest of these junks—that the Chinese termed *bao chuan* (treasure ships)—may have measured 121 metres (397 ft), and thousands of sailors were involved.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] At least seven well-documented expeditions were launched, each bigger and more expensive than the last.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The fleets visited Arabia, East Africa, India, Malay Archipelago, and Thailand (then called Siam), exchanging goods along the way.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] They presented gifts of gold, silver, porcelain, and silk; in return, received such novelties as ostriches, zebras, camels, ivory, and giraffes.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] After the emperor's death, Zheng He led a final expedition departing from Nanking in 1431 and returning to Beijing in 1433.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] It is likely this last expedition reached as far as Madagascar.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The travels were reported by Ma Huan, a Muslim voyager and translator who accompanied Zheng He on three of the expeditions, his account published as the *Yingya Shenglan* (Overall Survey of the Ocean's Shores) (1433).
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The voyages had a significant and lasting effect on the organization of a maritime network, using and creating nodes and conduits in its wake, thereby restructuring international and cross-cultural relationships and exchanges.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] It was especially impactful as no other polity had exerted naval dominance over all sectors of the Indian Ocean, prior to these voyages.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The Ming promoted alternative nodes as a strategy to establish control over the network.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] For instance, due to Chinese involvement, ports such as Malacca (in Southeast Asia), Cochin (Malabar Coast), and Malindi (Swahili Coast) had grown as key alternatives to other established ports.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The appearance of the Ming treasure fleet generated and intensified competition among contending polities and rivals, each seeking an alliance with the Ming.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The expeditions developed into a maritime trade enterprise, with imperial control over local markets and court-monitored transactions, generating revenue for China and its partners.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] They boosted regional trade and production, caused a supply shock in Eurasia and led to price spikes in Europe in the early 15th century.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The tributary relations promoted during the voyages manifested a trend toward cross-regional interconnections and early globalization in Asia and Africa.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Diplomatic relations were built on mutually beneficial maritime trade and China's strong naval presence in foreign waters, with Chinese naval superiority being a key factor in these interactions.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The voyages brought about the Western Ocean's regional integration and increase in international circulation of people, ideas, and goods.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] It provided a platform for cosmopolitan discourses, which took place in locations such as the ships of the Ming treasure fleet, the Ming capitals of Nanjing as well as Beijing, and the banquet receptions organized by the Ming court for foreign representatives.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Diverse groups of people from maritime countries congregated, interacted, and traveled together as the treasure fleet sailed from and to China.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] For the first time, the maritime region from China to Africa was under the dominance of a single imperial power and allowed for the creation of a cosmopolitan space.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] These long-distance journeys were not followed up, as the Ming dynasty retreated in the *haijin*, a policy of isolationism, having limited maritime trade.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 8th until the 15th century, the Republic of Venice and neighboring maritime republics held the monopoly of European trade with the Middle East.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The silk and spice trade, involving spices, incense, herbs, drugs, and opium, made these Mediterranean city-states phenomenally rich.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Spices were among the most expensive and demanded products of the Middle Ages, as they were used in medieval medicine, religious rituals, cosmetics, perfumery, and food additives and preservatives.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] They were imported from Asia and Africa.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Muslim traders dominated maritime routes throughout the Indian Ocean, tapping source regions in the Far East and shipping for trading emporiums in India, mainly Calicut, westward to Hormuz in the Persian Gulf and Jeddah in the Red Sea.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] From there, overland routes led to the Mediterranean.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Afterwards, the routes into Asia through the Black Sea and through Armenia and Persia became blocked by wars and banditry as the Mongol states disintegrated.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The trade route from the Persian Gulf to the Mediterranean by land is also dangerous due to the unstable territorial control of the Mamluk.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The trade from India went almost entirely into the Red Sea.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Nevertheless, European spices have not become more expensive as a result.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Forced to reduce activity in the Black Sea, and at war with Venice, the Genoese had turned to North African trade of wheat, olive oil and a search for silver and gold.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Europeans had a constant deficit in silver and gold, as it only went out, spent on eastern trade now cut off.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Several European mines were exhausted, The lack of bullion led to the development of a complex banking system to manage the risks in trade (the first state bank, *Banco di San Giorgio*, was founded in 1407 at Genoa).
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Sailing into the ports of Bruges and England, Genoese communities were then established in Portugal, who profited from their enterprise and financial expertise.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] European sailing had been primarily close to land cabotage, guided by portolan charts.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] These charts specified proven ocean routes guided by coastal landmarks: sailors departed from a known point, followed a compass heading, and tried to identify their location by its landmarks.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] For the first oceanic exploration Europeans used the compass, and advances in cartography and astronomy.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Arab navigational tools like the astrolabe and quadrant were used for celestial navigation.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The Muslim lands in Asia were more economically developed, had better infrastructure, despite Europe's economic changes brought by the Black Death, allowing for more freedoms.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The Islamic gunpowder empires concealed knowledge from European Christian traders about where lucrative locations such as Indonesia were.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1317, King Denis of Portugal made an agreement with Genoese merchant sailor Manuel Pessanha, appointing him first admiral of the Portuguese Navy, to defend the country against Muslim pirate raids.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Outbreaks of bubonic plague led to depopulation in the second half of the 14th century: only the sea offered alternatives, with most population settling in fishing and trading coastal areas.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1325 and 1357, Afonso IV of Portugal encouraged maritime commerce and ordered the first explorations.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The Canary Islands, already known to the Genoese, were claimed as officially discovered under the patronage of the Portuguese, but in 1344, Castile disputed them.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] To ensure their trade monopoly, Europeans, beginning with the Portuguese, attempted to install a Mediterranean system of trade which used military intimidation, to divert trade through ports they controlled; there it could be taxed.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1415, Ceuta, in North Africa, was conquered by the Portuguese aiming to control navigation of the African coast.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Young prince Henry the Navigator became aware of profit possibilities in the trans-Saharan trade routes.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] For centuries slave and gold trade routes linking West Africa with the Mediterranean passed over the Western Sahara Desert, controlled by the Moors.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] He invested in sponsoring voyages down the coast of Mauritania, gathering merchants, shipowners and stakeholders interested in new sea lanes.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Soon the Atlantic islands of Madeira (1419) and the Azores (1427) were reached.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The expedition leader who established settlements on Madeira, was explorer João Gonçalves Zarco.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Europeans did not know what lay beyond Cape Non (Cape Chaunar) on the African coast, and whether it was possible to return once crossed.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Nautical myths warned of monsters or an edge of the world, but Henry's navigation challenged such beliefs: starting in 1421, systematic sailing overcame it, reaching the difficult Cape Bojador that in 1434 one of Henry's captains, Gil Eanes, finally passed.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1440, caravels were extensively used for the exploration of the coast of Africa.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] This was an Iberian ship type, used for fishing, commerce and military purposes.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] It had a sternpost-mounted rudder, a shallow draft helpful in exploring coastlines, a good sailing performance, with a windward ability.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The lateen rig was less useful when sailing downwind – which explains Christopher Columbus (Italian: *Cristoforo Colombo*) re-rigging the *Niña* with square rig.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] For celestial navigation the Portuguese used the ephemerides, which experienced a remarkable diffusion in the 15th century.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] These were astronomical charts plotting the location of the stars.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Published in 1496 by Jewish astronomer and mathematician Abraham Zacuto, the Almanac Perpetuum included some of these tables for the movements of stars.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] These revolutionized navigation, allowing the calculation of latitude.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Exact longitude remained elusive from mariners for centuries.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Using the caravel, systematic exploration continued southerly, advancing one degree a year.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Senegal and Cape Verde Peninsula were reached in 1445 and in 1446, Álvaro Fernandes pushed on almost as far as present-day Sierra Leone.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1453, the fall of Constantinople to the Ottomans was a perceived blow to Christendom and established business links with the East.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The king, who had been inquiring of Genoese experts about a seaway to India, commissioned the Fra Mauro world map, which arrived in Lisbon in 1459.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1456, Diogo Gomes reached the Cape Verde archipelago.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In the next decade captains at the service of Prince Henry, discovered the remaining islands which were occupied during the 15th century.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The Gulf of Guinea was reached in the 1460s.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1460, Pedro de Sintra reached Sierra Leone.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Prince Henry died in November after which, given the meagre revenues, exploration was granted to Lisbon merchant Fernão Gomes in 1469, who in exchange for the monopoly of trade in the Gulf of Guinea had to explore 100 miles (161 kilometres) each year for five years.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] With his sponsorship, explorers João de Santarém, Pedro Escobar, Lopo Gonçalves, Fernão do Pó, and Pedro de Sintra made it beyond those goals.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] They reached the Southern Hemisphere and islands of the Gulf of Guinea, including São Tomé and Príncipe and Elmina in 1471.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] There, in what came to be called the "Gold Coast", in today's Ghana, a thriving alluvial gold trade was found among the natives, Arab and Berber traders.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1478, during the War of the Castilian Succession, near the coast at Elmina a large battle was fought between a Castilian armada of 35 caravels, and a Portuguese fleet for the hegemony of the Guinea trade.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The war ended with a Portuguese victory, followed by official recognition by the Catholic Monarchs of Portuguese sovereignty over most of the disputed West African territories embodied in the Treaty of Alcáçovas, 1479.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1481, João II decided to build São Jorge da Mina factory.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1482, the Congo River was explored by Diogo Cão, who in 1486 continued to Cape Cross (modern Namibia).
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The next crucial breakthrough was in 1488, when Bartolomeu Dias rounded the southern tip of Africa, which he named Cabo das Tormentas, "Cape of Storms", then sailing east as far as the mouth of the Great Fish River, proving the Indian Ocean was accessible from the Atlantic.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Pero da Covilhã, sent out travelling secretly overland, had reached Ethiopia having collected important information about the Red Sea and Quenia coast, suggesting a sea route to the Indies would soon be forthcoming.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Soon the cape was renamed by King John II of Portugal the *Cape of Good Hope*, because of the optimism engendered by the possibility of a sea route to India, proving false the view that had existed since Ptolemy that the Indian Ocean was land-locked.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Based on later stories of the phantom island known as Bacalao and the carvings on Dighton Rock some have speculated that Portuguese explorer João Vaz Corte-Real discovered Newfoundland in 1473, but the sources are considered unreliable.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal's Iberian rival, Castile, had begun to establish its rule over the Canary Islands in 1402, but became distracted by internal Iberian politics and the repelling of Islamic invasion attempts through most of the 15th century.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Following the unification of the crowns of Castile and Aragon, an emerging modern Spain became committed to the search for new trade routes overseas.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The Crown of Aragon had been an important maritime power, controlling territories in eastern Spain, southwestern France, major islands like Sicily, Malta, and the Kingdom of Naples and Sardinia, with mainland possessions as far as Greece.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1485 and 1488, Columbus had presented the project to king John II of Portugal, who rejected it.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] On 3 August 1492, Columbus departed from Palos de la Frontera.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Land was sighted on 12 October, and Columbus called the island *San Salvador* (Guanahani now in The Bahamas), in what he thought to be the East Indies.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus explored the north coast of Cuba and Hispaniola, by 5 December.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] He was received by the native cacique Guacanagari, who gave him permission to leave some men behind.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus left 39 and founded the settlement of *La Navidad* in what is now Haiti.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Before returning to Spain, he kidnapped 10-25 natives.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Only 7-8 of the 'Indians' arrived alive, but they made an impression on Seville.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] On 15 March 1493, he arrived in Barcelona, where he reported to Isabella and Ferdinand.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Word of his discovery of new lands spread throughout Europe.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus and other Spanish explorers were initially disappointed with their discoveries—unlike Africa or Asia, the Caribbean islanders had little to trade.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The islands thus became the focus of colonization efforts.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] It was not until the continent was explored that Spain found the wealth it had sought.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Shortly after Columbus's return from what would be called the "West Indies", a division of influence became necessary to avoid conflict between the Spaniards and Portuguese.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] It did not mention Portugal, which could not claim newly discovered lands east of the line.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] King John II of Portugal was displeased with the arrangement, feeling it gave him too little land—preventing him from reaching India, his goal.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] He negotiated directly with Ferdinand and Isabella to move the line west, allowing him to claim newly discovered lands east of it.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1494, the Treaty of Tordesillas divided the world between Portugal and Spain.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal gained control over Africa, Asia, and eastern South America (Brazil), encompassing everything outside Europe east of a line drawn 370 leagues west of the Cape Verde islands.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The Spaniards received everything west of this line, including the islands discovered by Columbus on his first voyage.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The dividing line, situated about halfway between Portuguese Cape Verde and Spanish discoveries in the Caribbean, split the known world of Atlantic islands evenly.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1500, Pedro Álvares Cabral, initially considering the Brazilian coast as a large island, claimed it for Portugal east of the dividing line.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] This claim was acknowledged by the Spaniards.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral, heading towards India, followed a corridor in the Atlantic negotiated by the treaty for favorable winds.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Later the Spanish territory would prove to include huge areas of the continental mainland of North and South America, though Portuguese-controlled Brazil would expand across the line, and settlements by other European powers ignored the treaty.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Little of the divided area had actually been seen by Europeans, as it was only divided by a geographical definition rather than control on the ground.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The desire to compete with the Ottoman Empire and Columbus's first voyage spurred further maritime exploration and, from 1497, other explorers headed west.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] That year John Cabot (Italian: *Giovanni Caboto*), also a commissioned Italian, got letters patent from King Henry VII of England.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Sailing from Bristol Cabot crossed the Atlantic from a northerly latitude hoping the voyage to the "West Indies" would be shorter and made landfall in North America, possibly Newfoundland.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Prior to Cabot's voyage, the furthest European expeditions in the North Atlantic had been by Norse explorers, who established settlements in Newfoundland and Greenland, which were abandoned in the 11th century and mid-15th century, respectively.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Merchants from Bristol had sponsored exploratory voyages in the 1480s, which did not report anything of note.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1499, João Fernandes Lavrador was licensed by the King of Portugal and together with Pero de Barcelos they first sighted Labrador, which was granted and named after him.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1499 and 1502, the brothers Gaspar and Miguel Corte Real explored and named the coasts of Greenland and Newfoundland.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Both explorations are noted in the 1502 Cantino planisphere.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1497, newly crowned King Manuel I of Portugal sent an exploratory fleet eastwards, fulfilling his predecessor's project of finding a route to the Indies.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In July 1499, news spread that the Portuguese had reached the "true Indies", as a letter was dispatched by the Portuguese king to the Spanish Monarchs.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The third expedition by Columbus in 1498 was the beginning of the first successful Spanish colonization in the West Indies, on the island of Hispaniola.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Despite growing doubts, Columbus refused to accept he had not reached the Indies.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] He discovered the mouth of the Orinoco River on the north coast of South America and thought the huge quantity of fresh water coming from it could only be from a continental land mass, which he was certain was Asia.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] As shipping between Seville and the West Indies grew, knowledge of the Caribbean islands, Central America and the northern coast of South America increased.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] One of these Spanish fleets, that of Alonso de Ojeda and Amerigo Vespucci in 1499–1500 reached land at the coast of what is now Guyana, where the two seem to have separated in opposite directions.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci sailed southward, discovering the mouth of the Amazon River in July 1499, and reaching 6°S, in present-day north east Brazil, before turning around.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Vicente Yáñez Pinzon was blown off course and reached what is now the northeast coast of Brazil on 26 January 1500, exploring as far south as the present-day state of Pernambuco.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] His fleet was the first to fully enter the Amazon River estuary, which he named *Saint Mary's River of the Freshwater Sea*.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The land was too far east for the Castilians to claim under the Treaty of Tordesillas, but the discovery created Castilian interest, with a second voyage by Pinzon in 1508 (the Pinzón–Solís voyage) and a voyage in 1515–1516 by a navigator of the 1508 expedition, Juan Díaz de Solís.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The 1515–1516 expedition was spurred on by reports of Portuguese exploration of the region.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] It ended when de Solís and some of his crew disappeared when exploring the River Plata in a boat, but what they found reignited Spanish interest, and colonization began in 1531.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In April 1500, the second Portuguese India Armada, headed by Pedro Álvares Cabral, with a crew of expert captains, encountered the Brazilian coast as it swung westward in the Atlantic while performing a large volta do mar to avoid becalming in the Gulf of Guinea.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] On 21 April, a mountain was seen and named *Monte Pascoal*, and on 22 April Cabral landed.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] On 25 April, the entire fleet sailed into the harbour they named *Porto Seguro*.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral perceived that the new land lay east of the line of Tordesillas, and sent an envoy to Portugal with the discovery in letters, including the letter of Pero Vaz de Caminha.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Believing the land to be an island, he named it Ilha de Vera Cruz.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] From the east coast, the fleet then turned eastward towards the southern tip of Africa and India.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral was the first captain to touch four continents, leading the first expedition that connected and united Europe, Africa, the New World, and Asia.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] At the invitation of King Manuel I of Portugal, Amerigo Vespucci participated as an observer in the exploratory voyages to the east coast of South America.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] It was understood that Columbus had not reached Asia but found a new continent, the Americas.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The Americas were named in 1507 by cartographers Martin Waldseemüller and Matthias Ringmann, after Amerigo Vespucci.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1501 to 1502, one of these Portuguese expeditions, led by Gonçalo Coelho, sailed south along the coast of South America to the bay of present-day Rio de Janeiro.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci's account states that the expedition reached the latitude "South Pole elevation 52° S", in the "cold" latitudes of what is now southern Patagonia, before turning back.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci wrote that they headed toward the southwest and south, following "a long, unbending coastline", apparently coincident with the southern South American coast.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] This seems controversial, since he changed part of his description in the subsequent letter, stating a shift, from about 32° S (Southern Brazil) to the south-southeast, to open sea, maintaining that they reached 50°/52° S.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1503, Binot Paulmier de Gonneville, challenging the Portuguese policy of *mare clausum*, led one of the earliest French Normand and Breton expeditions to Brazil.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] He intended to sail to the East Indies, but near the Cape of Good Hope, his ship was diverted to the west by a storm, and landed in the present-day state of Santa Catarina (southern Brazil), on 5 January 1504.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1511 to 1512, Portuguese captains João de Lisboa and Estevão de Fróis reached the River Plata estuary in present-day Uruguay and Argentina, and went as far south as the present-day Gulf of San Matias at 42°S.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The expedition reached a cape extending north to south which they called Cape of "Santa Maria" (Punta del Este); and after 40°S they found a "Cape" or "a point or place extending into the sea", and a "Gulf".
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] After they had navigated for nearly 300 km (186 mi) to round the cape, they again sighted the continent on the other side and steered towards the northwest, but a storm prevented them from making headway.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Driven away by the *Tramontane* or north wind, they retraced their course.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] Christopher de Haro, a Fleming of Sephardic origin, who would serve the Spanish Crown after 1516, believed the navigators had discovered a southern *strait* to west and Asia.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1519, an expedition sent by the Spanish Crown to find a way to Asia was led by the experienced Portuguese navigator Ferdinand Magellan.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] The fleet explored the rivers and bays as it charted the South American coast, until it found a way to the Pacific Ocean through the Strait of Magellan.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1524 to 1525, Aleixo Garcia, a Portuguese conquistador, led a private expedition of shipwrecked Castilian and Portuguese adventurers, who recruited about 2,000 Guaraní Indians.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] They explored the territories of present-day southern Brazil, Paraguay, and Bolivia, using the native trail network, the *Peabiru*.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p01] They were the first Europeans to cross the Chaco and reach the outer territories of the Inca Empire on the hills of the Andes.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Protected from direct Spanish competition by the Treaty of Tordesillas, Portuguese eastward exploration and colonization continued apace.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Twice, in 1485 and 1488, Portugal officially rejected Genoese Christopher Columbus's idea of reaching India by sailing westwards.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] King John II of Portugal's experts rejected it, for they held the opinion that Columbus's estimation of a travel distance of 2,400 miles (3,860 km) was low, and in part because Bartolomeu Dias departed in 1487 trying the rounding of the southern tip of Africa.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] They believed that sailing east would require a far shorter journey.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Dias's return from the Cape of Good Hope in 1488, and Pero da Covilhã's travel to Ethiopia overland indicated that the richness of the Indian Ocean was accessible from the Atlantic.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In July 1497, a small exploratory fleet of four ships and about 170 men left Lisbon under the command of Vasco da Gama.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] By December the fleet passed the Great Fish River—where Dias had turned back—and sailed into waters unknown to the Europeans.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Sailing into the Indian Ocean, da Gama entered a maritime region that had three different and well-developed trade circuits.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The one da Gama encountered connected Mogadishu on the east coast of Africa; Aden, at the tip of the Arabian peninsula; the Persian port of Hormuz; Cambay, in northwestern India; and Calicut, in southwestern India.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] On 20 May 1498, they arrived at Calicut.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The efforts of Vasco da Gama to get favorable trading conditions were hampered by the low value of their goods, compared with the valuable goods traded there.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Two years and two days after departure, Gama and a survivor crew of 55 men returned in glory to Portugal as the first ships to sail directly from Europe to India.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Da Gama's voyage is romanticized in the Os Lusíadas, an epic poem by fellow discovery-era traveler Luís de Camões.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The poem is widely regarded as Portugal's greatest literary achievement.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1500, a second, larger fleet of thirteen ships and about 1500 men were sent to India.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Under the command of Pedro Álvares Cabral, they made the first landfall on the Brazilian coast, giving Portugal its claim.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Later, in the Indian Ocean, one of Cabral's ships reached Madagascar (1501), which was partly explored by Tristão da Cunha in 1507; Mauritius was discovered in 1507, Socotra occupied in 1506.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In the same year Lourenço de Almeida landed in Sri Lanka, the eastern island named "Taprobane" in remote accounts of Alexander the Great's and 4th-century BC Greek geographer Megasthenes.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] On the Asiatic mainland, the first factories (trading-posts) were established at Kochi and Calicut (1501) and then Goa (1510).
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The Portuguese continued sailing eastward from India, entering a second existing circuit of the Indian Ocean trade, from Calicut and Quillon in India, to Southeast Asia, including Malacca and Palembang.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1511, Afonso de Albuquerque conquered Malacca for Portugal, then the center of Asian trade.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] East of Malacca, Albuquerque sent several diplomatic missions: Duarte Fernandes as the first European envoy to the Kingdom of Siam (modern Thailand).
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Learning the location of the so-called "spice islands", heretofore a secret from the Europeans, were the Spice Islands, mainly the Banda, then the world's only source of nutmeg and cloves.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Reaching these was the main purpose for the Portuguese voyages in the Indian Ocean.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Albuquerque sent an expedition led by António de Abreu to Banda (via Java and the Lesser Sunda Islands), where they were the first Europeans to arrive in early 1512, after taking a route through which they also reached first the islands of Buru, Ambon, and Seram.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In May 1513, Jorge Álvares, one of the Portuguese envoys, reached China.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Fernão Pires de Andrade visited Canton in 1517 and opened up trade with China.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] After a few decades, hostilities between the Portuguese and Chinese ceased and in 1557 the Chinese allowed the Portuguese to occupy Macau.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] To enforce a trade monopoly, Muscat and Hormuz in the Persian Gulf were seized by Afonso de Albuquerque in 1507 and in 1515, respectively.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] He also entered into diplomatic relations with Persia.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1513, while trying to conquer Aden, an expedition led by Albuquerque cruised the Red Sea inside the Bab al-Mandab and sheltered at Kamaran island.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1521, a force under António Correia conquered Bahrain, ushering in a period of almost 80 years of Portuguese rule of the Gulf archipelago.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In the Red Sea, Massawa was the most northerly point frequented by the Portuguese until 1541, when a fleet under Estevão da Gama penetrated as far as Suez.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1513, about 40 miles (64 kilometres) south of Acandí, in present-day Colombia, Spanish Vasco Núñez de Balboa heard unexpected news of an "other sea" rich in gold, which he received with great interest.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] With few resources and using information given by *caciques*, he journeyed across the Isthmus of Panama with 190 Spaniards, a few native guides, and a pack of dogs.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Balboa, using a brigantine and ten native canoe, explored the coast, facing battles and dense jungles.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] On 25 September, after crossing the Chucunaque River mountains, he became the first European to see the Pacific Ocean from the New World.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The expedition briefly navigated the Pacific, naming the bay *San Miguel* and the sea *Mar del Sur* (South Sea).
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Seeking gold, Balboa traversed cacique lands to the islands, naming the largest Isla Rica (now Isla del Rey) and the group *Archipiélago de las Perlas*, names still in use today.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1515 to 1516, the Spanish fleet led by Juan Díaz de Solís sailed down the east coast of South America as far as Río de la Plata, which Solís named shortly before he died while trying to find a passage to the "South Sea".
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] By 1516, several Portuguese navigators conflicting with King Manuel I of Portugal gathered in Seville to serve the newly crowned Charles I of Spain.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Among them were explorers Diogo and Duarte Barbosa, Estêvão Gomes, João Serrão, and Ferdinand Magellan, cartographers Jorge Reinel and Diogo Ribeiro, cosmographers Francisco and Ruy Faleiro and the Flemish merchant Christopher de Haro.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Ferdinand Magellan had sailed in India for Portugal up to 1513, when the Spice Islands were reached, and had kept contact with Francisco Serrão who was living there.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Magellan developed the theory that the Spice Islands were in the Tordesillas Spanish area, based on studies by Faleiro brothers.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Aware of the efforts of the Spanish to find a route to India by sailing west, Magellan presented his plan to Charles I of Spain.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The king and Christopher de Haro financed Magellan's expedition.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] A fleet was put together, and Spanish navigators such as Juan Sebastián Elcano joined the enterprise.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] On 10 August 1519, they departed from Seville with a fleet of five ships—the caravel flagship *Trinidad* under Magellan's command, and carracks *San Antonio*, *Concepcion*, *Santiago* and *Victoria*.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] They contained a crew of about 237 European men from several regions, with the goal of reaching the Spice Islands by travelling west, trying to reclaim it under Spain's economic and political sphere.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The fleet sailed south, avoiding Portuguese Brazil, and became the first to reach Tierra del Fuego.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Starting on 21 October, they navigated the 373-mile (600 km) Strait of Magellan, entering the Pacific on 28 November, which Magellan named Mar Pacífico for its calm waters.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] After crossing the Pacific, Magellan was killed in the Battle of Mactan in the Philippines.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Juan Sebastián Elcano completed the voyage, reaching the Spice Islands in 1521.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] On 6 September 1522, the *Victoria* returned to Spain, completing the first circumnavigation of the globe.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Of the original crew, only 18 men completed the circumnavigation; 17 returned later, including twelve captured by the Portuguese and five survivors of the Trinidad.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Antonio Pigafetta, a Venetian scholar, kept a detailed journal that is a key source of information about the voyage.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] This round-the-world voyage gave Spain valuable knowledge of the world and its oceans which later helped in the exploration and settlement of the Philippines.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Soon after Magellan's expedition, the Portuguese rushed to seize the surviving crew and built a fort in Ternate.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1525, Charles I of Spain sent another expedition westward to colonize the Spice Islands, claiming that they were in his zone of the Treaty of Tordesillas.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The fleet of seven ships and 450 men was led by García Jofre de Loaísa and included the most notable Spanish navigators: Juan Sebastián Elcano and Loaísa, who died then, and the young Andrés de Urdaneta.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Near the Strait of Magellan one of the ships was pushed south by a storm, reaching 56° S, where they thought seeing "*earth's end*": so Cape Horn was crossed for the first time.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The expedition reached the islands with great difficulty, docking at Tidore.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The conflict with the Portuguese established in nearby Ternate was inevitable, starting nearly a decade of skirmishes.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] As there was not a set eastern limit to the Tordesillas line, both kingdoms organized meetings to resolve the issue.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1524 to 1529, Portuguese and Spanish experts met at Badajoz-Elvas trying to find the exact location of the antimeridian of Tordesillas, which would divide the world into two equal hemispheres.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Each crown appointed three astronomers and cartographers, three pilots, and three mathematicians.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Lopo Homem, Portuguese cartographer and cosmographer was on the board, along with cartographer Diogo Ribeiro of the Spanish delegation.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The board met several times without reaching an agreement: the knowledge at that time was insufficient for an accurate calculation of longitude, and each group gave the islands to its sovereign.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The issue was settled only in 1529, after a long negotiation, with the signing of Treaty of Zaragoza, which allocated the Spice Islands to Portugal and the Philippines to Spain.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1525 to 1528, Portugal sent several expeditions around the Spice Islands.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Gomes de Sequeira and Diogo da Rocha were sent north by the governor of Ternate Jorge de Menezes, being the first Europeans to reach the Caroline Islands, which they named *Islands of Gomes de Sequeira*.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1526, Jorge de Meneses docked on Biak and Waigeo islands, Papua New Guinea.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Based on these explorations stands the theory of Portuguese discovery of Australia, one among several competing theories about the early discovery of Australia, supported by Australian historian Kenneth McIntyre, stating it was discovered by Cristóvão de Mendonça and Gomes de Sequeira.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1527, Hernán Cortés fitted out a fleet to find new lands in the "South Sea" (Pacific Ocean), asking his cousin Álvaro de Saavedra Cerón to take charge.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] On 31 October 1527, Saavedra sailed from New Spain, crossing the Pacific and touring the north of New Guinea, then named *Isla de Oro*.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In October 1528, one of the vessels reached the Spice Islands.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In his attempt to return to New Spain he was diverted by the northeast trade winds, which threw him back, so he tried sailing back down, to the south.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] He returned to New Guinea and sailed northeast, where he sighted the Marshall Islands and the Admiralty Islands, but again was surprised by the winds, which brought him a third time to the Moluccas.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] This westbound return route was hard to find but was eventually discovered by Andrés de Urdaneta in 1565.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Rumors of undiscovered islands northwest of Hispaniola reached Spain by 1511, ushering King Ferdinand's interest in forestalling further exploration.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] While the Portuguese were making huge gains in the Indian Ocean, the Spanish invested in exploring inland in search of gold and other valuable resources.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The members of these expeditions, the conquistadors, were not soldiers in an army, but more like soldiers of fortune; they came from a variety of backgrounds including artisans, merchants, clergy, lawyers, lesser nobility and a few freed slaves.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] They usually supplied their own equipment or were extended credit to purchase it in exchange for a share in profits.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] They usually had no professional military training, but a number of them had previous experience on other expeditions.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In the Americas, the Spanish encountered large indigenous empires and formed alliances with indigenous people through small expeditions.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] After establishing Spanish sovereignty and discovering wealth, the crown focused on implementing Spanish state and church institutions.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] A key element was the 'spiritual conquest' through Christian evangelization.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The initial economy relied on a tribute and forced labor under the *encomienda* system.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The discovery of vast silver deposits transformed both the colonial economies of Mexico and Peru and Spain's economy.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] With global trade networks and valuable American crops, Spain's economy strengthened, enhancing its status as a world power.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] During this time, pandemics of European diseases such as smallpox decimated the indigenous populations.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1512, to reward Juan Ponce de León for exploring Puerto Rico in 1508, King Ferdinand urged him to seek these new lands.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] He would become governor of discovered lands but was to finance himself all exploration.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] With three ships and about 200 men, Léon set out from Puerto Rico in March 1513.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In April, they sighted land and named it *La Florida*—because it was Easter (Florida) season—believing it was an island, becoming credited as the first European to land in the continent.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The arrival location has been disputed between St.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Augustine, Ponce de León Inlet and Melbourne Beach.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] They headed south for further exploration and on 8 April encountered a current so strong that it pushed them backward: this was the first encounter with the Gulf Stream that would soon become the primary route for eastbound ships leaving the Spanish Indies bound for Europe.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] They explored down the coast reaching Biscayne Bay, Dry Tortugas and then sailing southwest in an attempt to circle Cuba to return, reaching Grand Bahama on July.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1517, Cuba's governor Diego Velázquez de Cuéllar commissioned a fleet under the command of Hernández de Córdoba to explore the Yucatán Peninsula.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] They reached the coast where Mayans invited them to land.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] They were attacked at night and only a remnant of the crew returned.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Velázquez then commissioned another expedition led by his nephew Juan de Grijalva, who sailed south along the coast to Tabasco, part of the Aztec Empire.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1518, Velázquez gave the mayor of the capital of Cuba, Hernán Cortés, the command of an expedition to secure the interior of Mexico but, due to an old gripe between them, revoked the charter.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In February 1519, Cortés went ahead anyway, in an act of open mutiny.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] With about 11 ships, 500 men, 13 horses, and a small number of cannons he landed in Yucatán, in Mayan territory, claiming the land for the Spanish crown.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] From Trinidad he proceeded to Tabasco and won a battle against the natives.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Among the vanquished was Marina (La Malinche), his future mistress, who knew both (Aztec) Nahuatl language and Maya, becoming a valuable interpreter and counsellor.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In July, his men took over Veracruz and he placed himself under direct orders of new king Charles I of Spain.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] There Cortés asked for a meeting with Aztec emperor Moctezuma II, who repeatedly refused.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] They headed to Tenochtitlan and on the way made alliances with several tribes.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In October, accompanied by about 3,000 Tlaxcaltec they marched to Cholula, the second largest city in central Mexico.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Either to instill fear upon the Aztecs waiting for him or (as he later claimed) wishing to make an example when he feared native treachery, they massacred thousands of unarmed members of the nobility gathered at the central plaza and partially burned the city.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] On 8 November, Cortés and his large army were welcomed by Moctezuma II in Tenochtitlan, who hoped to learn about them to eventually defeat them.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Moctezuma gave lavish gifts, which led Cortés to plunder the city.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Cortés claimed the Aztecs saw him as an emissary or incarnation of the god Quetzalcōātl, though this is contested by few historians.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Upon learning that his men had been attacked on the coast, Cortés took Moctezuma hostage in his palace, demanding tribute for King Charles.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Meanwhile, Velasquez sent another expedition, led by Pánfilo de Narváez, to oppose Cortès, arriving in Mexico in April 1520 with 1,100 men.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Cortés left 200 men in Tenochtitlan and took the rest to confront Narvaez, whom he overcame, convincing his men to join him.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In Tenochtitlán, one of Cortés's lieutenants committed a massacre in the Great Temple, triggering local rebellion.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Cortés speedily returned, attempting the support of Moctezuma but the Aztec emperor was killed, possibly stoned by his subjects.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The Spaniards fled for Tlaxcala during the *Noche Triste*, where they managed a narrow escape while their back guard was massacred.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Much of the treasure looted was lost during this panicked escape.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] After a battle in Otumba they reached Tlaxcala, having lost 870 men.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Having prevailed with the assistance of allies and reinforcements from Cuba, Cortés besieged Tenochtitlán and captured its ruler Cuauhtémoc in August 1521.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] As the Aztec Empire ended, he claimed the city for Spain and renamed it Mexico City.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] A first attempt to explore western South America was undertaken in 1522 by Pascual de Andagoya.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Native South Americans told him about a gold-rich territory on a river called Pirú.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Having reached San Juan River (Colombia), Andagoya fell ill and returned to Panama, where he spread the news about "Pirú" as the legendary El Dorado.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] These, along with the accounts of the success of Hernán Cortés, caught the attention of Pizarro.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Francisco Pizarro had accompanied Balboa in the crossing of the Isthmus of Panama.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1524, he formed a partnership with priest Hernando de Luque and soldier Diego de Almagro to explore the south, agreeing to divide the profits.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] They dubbed the enterprise the "*Empresa del Levante*": Pizarro would command, Almagro would provide military and food supplies, and Luque would be in charge of finances and additional provisions.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] On 13 September 1524, the first of three expeditions set out to conquer Peru with 80 men and 40 horses.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The venture failed, halting in Colombia due to bad weather, hunger, and conflicts with locals; Almagro lost an eye.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Their route was marked by *Puerto Deseado* (desired port), *Puerto del Hambre* (port of hunger), and *Puerto quemado* (burned port).
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Two years later, a second expedition began with reluctant permission from the Governor of Panama.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In August 1526, they departed with two ships, 160 men, and horses.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Upon reaching the San Juan River, Pizarro explored swampy coasts, while Almagro sought reinforcements.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro's pilot, sailing south and crossing the equator, captured a raft from Tumbes.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] To his surprise, the raft carried coveted textiles, ceramics, gold, silver, and emeralds, becoming the expedition's main focus.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Almagro later joined with reinforcements, and despite challenging conditions, they reached Atacames, where a sizable native population under Inca rule was observed, though they did not land.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro, safe near the coast, sent Almagro and Luque for reinforcements with proof of the rumoured gold.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The new governor rejected a third expedition, ordering everyone back to Panama.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Almagro and Luque seized the chance to rejoin Pizarro.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] At *Isla de Gallo*, Pizarro drew a line, presenting the choice between Peru's riches and Panama's poverty.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Thirteen men, The Famous Thirteen, stayed and headed to *La Isla Gorgona*, staying seven months until provisions arrived.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] They sailed south and by April 1528, reached northwestern Peru's Tumbes region, warmly received by the *Tumpis*.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro's men reported incredible riches, llama sightings, and the natives named them "Children of the Sun" for their fair complexion and brilliant armour.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] They decided to return to Panama to prepare a final expedition, sailing south through named territories like Cabo Blanco, port of Payta, Sechura, Punta de Aguja, Santa Cruz, and Trujillo, reaching the ninth degree south.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In the spring of 1528, Pizarro sailed for Spain, where he had an interview with king Charles I.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The king heard of his expeditions in lands rich in gold and silver and promised to support him.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The *Capitulación de Toledo* authorized Pizarro to proceed with the conquest of Peru.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro was then able to convince many friends and relatives to join: his brothers Hernándo Pizarro, Juan Pizarro, Gonzalo Pizarro, and also Francisco de Orellana, who would later explore the Amazon River, as well as his cousin Pedro Pizarro.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro's third and final expedition left Panama for Peru on 27 December 1530.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] With three ships and one hundred and eighty men, they landed near Ecuador and sailed to Tumbes, finding the place destroyed.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] They entered the interior and established the first Spanish settlement in Peru, San Miguel de Piura.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] One of the men returned with an Incan envoy and an invitation for a meeting.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Since the last meeting, the Inca had begun a civil war and Atahualpa had been resting in northern Peru following the defeat of his brother Huáscar.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] After marching for two months, they approached Atahualpa.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] He refused the Spanish, saying he would be "no man's tributary".
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] There were fewer than 200 Spanish to his 80,000 soldiers, but Pizarro attacked and won against the Incan army in the Battle of Cajamarca, taking Atahualpa captive at the so-called Ransom Room.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Despite fulfilling his promise of filling one room with gold and two with silver, he was convicted for killing his brother and plotting against Pizarro, and was executed.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] After the Spanish had sealed the conquest of Peru, Jauja in fertile Mantaro Valley was established as Peru's provisional capital, but it was too far up in the mountains, and Pizarro founded the city of Lima on 18 January 1535, which Pizarro considered one of the most important acts in his life.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1543, three Portuguese traders accidentally became the first Westerners to reach and trade with Japan.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] According to Fernão Mendes Pinto, who claimed to be in this journey, they arrived at Tanegashima, where the locals were impressed by firearms that would be immediately made by the Japanese on a large scale.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The Spanish conquest of the Philippines was ordered by Philip II of Spain, and Andrés de Urdaneta was the designated commander.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Urdaneta agreed to accompany the expedition but refused to command and Miguel López de Legazpi was appointed instead.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The expedition set sail in November 1564.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] After spending some time on the islands, Legazpi sent Urdaneta back to find a better return route.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Urdaneta set sail from San Miguel on the island of Cebu on 1 June 1565, but was obliged to sail as far as 38 degrees North latitude to obtain favorable winds.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] He reasoned that the trade winds of the Pacific might move in a gyre as the Atlantic winds did.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] If in the Atlantic, ships made the *Volta do mar* to pick up winds that would bring them back from Madeira, then, he reasoned, by sailing far to the north before heading east, he would pick up trade winds to bring him back to North America.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] His hunch paid off, and he hit the coast near Cape Mendocino, California, then followed the coast south.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The ship reached the port of Acapulco, on 8 October 1565, having traveled 12,000 miles (19,000 kilometres) in 130 days.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Fourteen of his crew died; only Urdaneta and Felipe de Salcedo, nephew of López de Legazpi, had strength enough to cast the anchors.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Thus, a cross-Pacific Spanish route was established, between Mexico and the Philippines.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] For a long time, these routes were used by the Manila galleons, thereby creating a trade link joining China, the Americas, and Europe via the combined trans-Pacific and trans-Atlantic routes.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] European nations outside Iberia did not recognize the Treaty of Tordesillas between Portugal and Castile, nor did they recognize Pope Alexander VI's donation of the Spanish finds in the New World.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] France, the Netherlands, and England each had a long maritime tradition and had been engaging in privateering.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Despite Iberian protections, the new technologies and maps soon made their way north.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] After the marriage of Henry VIII of England and Catherine of Aragon failed to produce a male heir and Henry failed to obtain a papal dispensation to annul his marriage, he broke with the Roman Catholic Church and established himself as head of the Church of England.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] This added religious conflict to political conflict.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] When much of The Netherlands became Protestant, it sought political and religious independence from Catholic Spain.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1568, the Dutch rebelled against the rule of Philip II of Spain leading to the Eighty Years' War.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The war between England and Spain also broke out.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1580, Philip II became King of Portugal, as heir to its Crown.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Although he ruled Portugal and its empire as separate from the Spanish Empire, the union of the crowns produced a Catholic superpower, which England and the Netherlands challenged.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In the eighty-year Dutch War of Independence, Philip's troops conquered the important trading cities of Bruges and Ghent.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Antwerp, then the most important port in the world, fell in 1585.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The Protestant population was given two years to settle affairs before leaving the city.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Those were mainly skilled craftsmen, rich merchants of the port cities and refugees that fled religious persecution, particularly Sephardic Jews from Portugal and Spain and, later, the Huguenots from France.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The Pilgrim Fathers also spent time there before going to the New World.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] This mass immigration was an important driving force: a small port in 1585, Amsterdam quickly transformed into one of the most important commercial centres in the world.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] After the failure of the Spanish Armada in 1588, there was a huge expansion of maritime trade even though the defeat of the English Armada would confirm the naval supremacy of the Spanish navy over the emergent competitors.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch maritime power rose quickly as Dutch sailors, skilled in navigation and mapmaking, engaged with Portuguese voyages.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1592, Cornelis de Houtman gathered information on the Spice Islands in Lisbon.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The same year, Jan Huyghen van Linschoten published a detailed travel report in Amsterdam, providing navigation instructions for reaching the East Indies and Japan.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Following this, Houtman led the Dutch's first exploratory voyage, discovering a new route from Madagascar to the Sunda Strait and securing a treaty with the Banten Sultan.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The Dutch also demonstrated their maritime strength by seizing Malacca from Portugal in 1641, following a series of battles that began in 1602.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch and British interest, fed on new information, led to a movement of commercial expansion, and the foundation of English (1600) and Dutch (1602) chartered companies.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch, French, and English sent ships which flouted the Portuguese monopoly, concentrated mostly on the coastal areas, which proved unable to defend against such a vast and dispersed venture.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The 1497 English expedition authorized by Henry VII of England was led by Italian Venetian John Cabot (Giovanni Caboto); it was the first of a series of French and English missions exploring North America.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Mariners from the Italian peninsula played an important role in early explorations, most especially Genoese mariner Christopher Columbus.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] With its major conquests of central Mexico and Peru and discoveries of silver, Spain put limited efforts into exploring the northern part of the Americas; its resources were concentrated in Central and South America where more wealth had been found.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] These other European expeditions were initially motivated by the same idea as Columbus, namely a westerly shortcut to the Asian mainland.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] After the existence of "another ocean" (the Pacific) was confirmed by Balboa in 1513, there still remained the motivation of potentially finding an oceanic Northwest Passage for Asian trade.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] This was not discovered until the early twentieth century, but other possibilities were found, although nothing on the scale of the spectacular ones of the Spanish.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In the early 17th century colonists from a number of Northern European states began to settle on the east coast of North America.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1524, Italian Giovanni da Verrazzano sailed under the authority of Francis I of France, who was motivated by indignation over the division of the world between Portuguese and Spanish.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Verrazzano explored the Atlantic Coast of North America, from South Carolina to Newfoundland, and was the first recorded European to visit what would later become the Virginia Colony and the United States.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In the same year Estêvão Gomes, a Portuguese cartographer who had sailed in Ferdinand Magellan's fleet, explored Nova Scotia, sailing South through Maine, where he entered what is now New York Harbor, the Hudson River and eventually reached Florida in August 1525.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] As a result of his expedition, the 1529 Diogo Ribeiro world map outlines the East coast of North America almost perfectly.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Europeans explored the Pacific Coast beginning in the mid-16th century.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Spaniard Francisco de Ulloa explored the Pacific coast of present-day Mexico including the Gulf of California, proving that Baja California was a peninsula.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Despite his report based on first-hand information, the myth persisted in Europe that California was an island.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] His account provided the first recorded use of the name "California".
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] João Rodrigues Cabrilho, a Portuguese navigator sailing for the Spanish Crown, was the first European to set foot in California, landing on 28 September 1542, on the shores of San Diego Bay and claiming California for Spain.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] He also landed on San Miguel, one of the Channel Islands, and continued as far north as Point Reyes on the mainland.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] After his death, the crew continued exploring as far north as Oregon.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The English privateer Francis Drake sailed along the coast in 1579 north of Cabrillo's landing site while circumnavigating the world.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake had a long and largely successful career attacking Spanish settlements in the Caribbean islands and the mainland so for the English, he was a great hero and fervent Protestant, but for the Spanish, he was "a frightening monster".
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake played a major role in the defeat of the Spanish Armada in 1588 but led an armada himself to the Spanish Caribbean that was unsuccessful in dislodging the Spanish.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] On 5 June 1579, the ship briefly made first landfall at South Cove, Cape Arago, just south of Coos Bay, Oregon, and then sailed south while searching for a suitable harbor to repair his damaged ship.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] On 17 June, Drake and his crew found a protected cove when they landed on the Pacific coast of what is now Northern California near Point Reyes.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] While ashore, he claimed the area for Queen Elizabeth I of England as Nova Albion or New Albion.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] To document and assert his claim, Drake posted an engraved plate of brass to claim sovereignty for Queen Elizabeth and her successors on the throne.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake's landfalls on the west coast of North America are one small part of his 1577–1580 circumnavigation of the globe, the first captain of his own ship to do so.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake died in 1596 off the coast of Panama, following injuries from a raid.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] He explored the Hudson River and laid the foundation for Dutch colonization of the region.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Hudson's final expedition ranged farther north in search of the Northwest Passage, leading to his discovery of the Hudson Strait and Hudson Bay.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] After wintering in James Bay, Hudson tried to press on with his voyage in the spring of 1611, but his crew mutinied and they cast him adrift.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] France, the Netherlands, and England sought a sea route to Asia after finding none through Africa or South America.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] With no route through the Americas, they focused on northern passages, driving European exploration of the Arctic coasts.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The idea of a link between the Atlantic and Pacific was first proposed by Russian diplomat Gerasimov in 1525, though Russian Pomors had explored parts of the route as early as the 11th century.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1553, English explorer Hugh Willoughby with chief pilot Richard Chancellor were sent out with three vessels in search of a passage by London's Company of Merchant Adventurers to New Lands.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] During the voyage across the Barents Sea, Willoughby thought he saw islands to the north, and islands called Willoughby's Land were shown on maps published by Plancius and Mercator into the 1640s.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The vessels were separated by "terrible whirlwinds" in the Norwegian Sea and Willoughby sailed into a bay near the present border between Finland and Russia.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] His ships with the frozen crews, including Captain Willoughby and his journal, were found by Russian fishermen a year later.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Richard Chancellor was able to drop anchor in the White Sea and make his way overland to Moscow and Ivan the Terrible's court, opening trade with Russia and the Company of Merchant Adventurers became the Muscovy Company.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In June 1576, English mariner Martin Frobisher led an expedition consisting of three ships and 35 men to search for a north-west passage around North America.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The voyage was supported by the Muscovy Company, the same merchants that hired Hugh Willoughby to find a northeast passage above Russia.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Violent storms sank one ship and forced another to turn back but Frobisher and the remaining ship reached the coast of Labrador in July.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] A few days later they came upon the mouth of what is now Frobisher Bay.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Frobisher believed it to be the entrance to a north-west passage and named it Frobisher's Strait and claimed Baffin Island for Queen Elizabeth.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] After some preliminary exploration, Frobisher returned to England.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] He commanded two subsequent voyages in 1577 and 1578 but failed to find the hoped-for passage.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Frobisher brought to England his ships laden with ore, but it was found to be worthless and damaged his reputation as an explorer.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] He remains an important early historical figure in Canada.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] On 5 June 1594, Dutch cartographer Willem Barentsz departed from Texel in a fleet of three ships to enter the Kara Sea, with the hopes of finding the Northeast Passage above Siberia.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] At Williams Island the crew encountered a polar bear for the first time.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] They managed to bring it on board, but the bear rampaged and was killed.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Barentsz reached the west coast of Novaya Zemlya and followed it northward, before being forced to turn back in the face of large icebergs.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The following year, Prince Maurice of Orange named him chief pilot of a new expedition of six ships, loaded with merchant wares that the Dutch hoped to trade with China.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The party came across Samoyed "wild men" but eventually turned back upon discovering the Kara Sea frozen.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1596, the States-General offered a high reward for anybody who *successfully* navigated the Northeast Passage.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The Town Council of Amsterdam purchased and outfitted two small ships, captained by Jan Rijp and Jacob van Heemskerck, to search for the elusive channel, under the command of Barents.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] They set off in May, and in June discovered Bear Island and Spitsbergen, sighting its northwest coast.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] They saw a large bay, later called Raudfjorden and entered Magdalenefjorden, which they named *Tusk Bay*, sailing into the northern entrance of Forlandsundet, which they called *Keerwyck*, but were forced to turn back because of a shoal.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] On 28 June they rounded the northern point of Prins Karls Forland, which they named *Vogelhoek*, on account of a large number of birds, and sailed south, passing Isfjorden and Bellsund, which were labelled on Barentsz's chart as *Grooten Inwyck* and *Inwyck*.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The ships once again reached Bear Island on 1 July, which led to a disagreement.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] They parted ways, with Barentsz continuing northeast, while Rijp headed north.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Barentsz reached Novaya Zemlya and, to avoid becoming entrapped in ice, headed for the Kara Strait but became stuck within the icebergs and floes.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Stranded, the 16-man crew was forced to spend the winter on the ice.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] The crew used lumber from their ship to build a lodge they called *Het Behouden Huys* (The Kept House).
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Dealing with extreme cold, they used merchant fabrics to make additional blankets and clothing and caught Arctic foxes in primitive traps, as well as polar bears.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] When June arrived, and the ice had still not loosened its grip on the ship, scurvy-ridden survivors took two small boats out into the sea.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Barentsz died at sea on 20 June 1597, while studying charts.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] It took seven more weeks for the boats to reach Kola where they were rescued by a Russian merchant vessel.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Only 12 crewmen remained, reaching Amsterdam in November.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Two of Barentsz' crewmembers later published their journals, Jan Huyghen van Linschoten, who had accompanied him on the first two voyages, and Gerrit de Veer who had acted as the ship's carpenter on the last.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Juan Fernández, sailing from Chile in 1576, claimed he had discovered the Southern Continent.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Luís Vaz de Torres, a Galician navigator working for the Spanish Crown, proved the existence of a passage south of New Guinea, now known as Torres Strait.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Pedro Fernandes de Queirós, a Portuguese navigator sailing for the Spanish Crown, saw a large island south of New Guinea in 1606, which he named *Austrialia del Espiritu Santo* (transl.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Southern-Austrian Land of the Holy Spirit).
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] He represented this to the King of Spain as the *Terra Australis incognita*, but it was present-day Vanuatu rather than Australia or Antarctica.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch navigator and colonial governor, Willem Janszoon sailed from the Netherlands for the East Indies for the third time on 18 December 1603, as captain of *Duyfken* (or *Duijfken*, meaning 'Little Dove'), one of twelve ships of the great fleet of Steven van der Hagen.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Once in the Indies, Janszoon was sent to search for other outlets of trade, particularly in "the great land of Nova Guinea and other East and Southlands".
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] On 18 November 1605, *Duyfken* sailed from Banten to the coast of western New Guinea.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Janszoon then crossed the eastern end of the Arafura Sea, without becoming aware of the Torres Strait, into the Gulf of Carpentaria.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] On 26 February 1606, he made landfall at the Pennefather River on the western shore of Cape York in Queensland, near the modern town of Weipa.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] This is the first recorded European landfall on the Australian continent.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Janszoon proceeded to chart some 320 kilometres (199 mi) of the coastline, which he thought was a southerly extension of New Guinea.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1615, Jacob Le Maire and Willem Schouten's rounding of Cape Horn proved that Tierra del Fuego was a relatively small island.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1642 to 1644, Abel Tasman, also a Dutch explorer and merchant in the service of the VOC, circumnavigated New Holland proving that Australia was not part of the mythical southern continent.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] He was the first known European expedition to reach the islands of Van Diemen's Land (now Tasmania) and New Zealand and to sight the Fiji islands, which he did in 1643.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p02] Tasman, his navigator Visscher, and his merchant Gilsemans also mapped substantial portions of Australia, New Zealand, and the Pacific islands.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] In the mid-16th century, the Tsardom of Russia conquered the Tatar khanates of Kazan and Astrakhan, thus annexing the entire Volga region and opening the way to the Ural Mountains.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] The colonization of the new easternmost lands of Russia and further onslaught eastward was led by the rich merchants Stroganovs.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Ivan the Terrible granted vast estates near the Urals as well as tax privileges to Anikey Stroganov, who organized large-scale migration to these lands.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] The Stroganovs developed farming, hunting, saltworks, fishing, and ore mining on the Urals and established trade with Siberian tribes.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Around 1577, Semyon Stroganov and other sons of Anikey Stroganov hired a Cossack leader called Yermak to protect their lands from the attacks of Khan Kuchum.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] By 1580, Stroganovs and Yermak came up with the idea of a military expedition to Siberia, to fight Kuchum in his own land.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1581, Yermak began his voyage into the depths of Siberia.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] After a few victories over the Khan's army, Yermak's people defeated the main forces of Kuchum on Irtysh River in the three-day Battle of Chuvash Cape in 1582.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] The remains of the Khan's army retreated to the steppes, and thus Yermak captured the Khanate of Sibir, including its capital Qashliq near modern Tobolsk.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Kuchum still was strong and suddenly attacked Yermak in 1585 in the dead of night, killing most of his people.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Yermak was wounded and tried to swim across the Wagay River (Irtysh's tributary), but drowned under the weight of his own chain mail.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] The Cossacks had to withdraw from Siberia completely, but thanks to Yermak's having explored all the main river routes in West Siberia, Russians successfully reclaimed all his conquests just several years later.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] In the early 17th century, the eastward movement of Russians was slowed by the internal problems in the country during the Time of Troubles.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Very soon, exploration and colonization of the huge territories of Siberia resumed, led mostly by Cossacks hunting for valuable furs and ivory.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] While Cossacks came from the Southern Urals, another wave of Russians came by the Arctic Ocean.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] These were Pomors from the Russian North, who already had been making fur trade with Mangazeya in the north of Western Siberia for quite a long time.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1607, the settlement of Turukhansk was founded on the northern Yenisey River, near the mouth of Lower Tunguska.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1619, Yeniseysk ostrog was founded on the mid-Yenisey at the mouth of the Upper Tunguska.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Between 1620 and 1624, a group of fur hunters led by Demid Pyanda left Turukhansk and explored some 1,430 miles (2,300 kilometres) of the Lower Tunguska, wintering in the proximity of the Vilyuy and Lena Rivers.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] According to later legendary accounts (folktales collected a century after the fact), Pyanda discovered the Lena.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] He allegedly explored some 1,500 miles (2,400 kilometres) of its length, reaching as far as central Yakutia.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] He returned up the Lena until it became too rocky and shallow, and portaged to the Angara River.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] In this way, Pyanda may have become the first Russian to meet Yakuts and Buryats.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] He built new boats and explored some 870 miles (1,400 kilometres) of the Angara, finally reaching Yeniseysk and discovering that the Angara (a Buryat name) and Upper Tunguska (Verkhnyaya Tunguska, as initially known by Russians) are one and the same river.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1627, Pyotr Beketov was appointed Yenisei voevoda in Siberia.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] He successfully carried out the voyage to collect taxes from the Zabaykalye Buryats, becoming the first Russian to step in Buryatia.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] He founded the first Russian settlement there, Rybinsky ostrog.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Beketov was sent to the Lena River in 1631, where in 1632 he founded Yakutsk and sent his Cossacks to explore the Aldan River and farther down the Lena, to found new fortresses, and to collect taxes.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Yakutsk soon turned into a major starting point for further Russian expeditions eastward, southward and northward.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Maksim Perfilyev, who earlier had been one of the founders of Yeniseysk, founded Bratsk ostrog on the Angara in 1631.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1638, Perfilyev became the first Russian to step into Transbaikalia, travelling there from Yakutsk.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1643, Kurbat Ivanov led a group of Cossacks from Yakutsk to the south of the Baikal Mountains and discovered Lake Baikal, visiting its Olkhon Island.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Ivanov later made the first chart and description of Baikal.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1639, a group of explorers led by Ivan Moskvitin became the first Russians to reach the Pacific Ocean and to discover the Sea of Okhotsk, having built a winter camp on its shore at the Ulya River mouth.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] The Cossacks learned from the locals about the large Amur River far to the south.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1640, they apparently sailed south, and explored the south-eastern shores of the Okhotsk Sea, perhaps reaching the mouth of the Amur River and possibly discovering the Shantar Islands on their way back.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Based on Moskvitin's account, Kurbat Ivanov drew the first Russian map of the Far East in 1642.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1643, Vassili Poyarkov crossed the Stanovoy Range and reached the upper Zeya River in the country of the Daurs, who were paying tribute to the Manchus.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] After wintering, in 1644, Poyarkov pushed down the Zeya and became the first Russian to reach the Amur River.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] He sailed down the Amur and finally discovered the mouth of that great river from land.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Since his Cossacks provoked the enmity of the locals behind, Poyarkov chose a different way back.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] They built boats and in 1645, sailed along the Sea of Okhotsk coast to the Ulya River and spent the next winter in the huts that had been built by Ivan Moskvitin six years earlier.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1644, Mikhail Stadukhin discovered the Kolyma River and founded Srednekolymsk.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] A merchant named Fedot Alekseyevich Popov organized a further expedition eastward, and Semyon Dezhnyov became a captain of one of the kochi.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1648, they sailed from Srednekolymsk down to the Arctic and after some time they rounded Cape Dezhnyov, thus becoming the first explorers to pass through the Bering Strait and discover Chukotka and the Bering Sea.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] All their Kochi and most of their men (including Popov himself) were lost in storms and clashes with the natives.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] A small group led by Dezhnyov reached the mouth of the Anadyr River and sailed up it in 1649, having built new boats from the wreckage.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] They founded Anadyrsk and were stranded there until Stadukhin found them, coming from Kolyma by land.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Subsequently, Stadukhin set off south in 1651 and discovered Penzhin Bay on the northern coast of the Okhotsk Sea.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] He also may have explored the western shores of Kamchatka.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] From 1649 to 1650, Yerofey Khabarov became the second Russian to explore the Amur River.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Through the Olyokma, Tungir, and Shilka Rivers he reached Amur (Dauriya), returned to Yakutsk and then back to Amur with a larger force in 1650–1653.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] This time he was met with armed resistance.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] He built winter quarters at Albazin, then sailed down Amur and found Achansk, which preceded the present-day Khabarovsk, defeating or evading large armies of Daurs, Manchus, Chinese, and Koreans on his way.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] He charted the Amur in his *Draft of the Amur river*.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Subsequently, the Russians held on to the Amur region until 1689, when by the Treaty of Nerchinsk this land was assigned to the Qing Empire.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] It was returned by the Treaty of Aigun in 1858.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] From 1659 to 1665, Kurbat Ivanov was the next head of Anadyrsky ostrog after Semyon Dezhnev.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1660, he sailed from Anadyr Bay to Cape Dezhnyov.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] By the mid-17th century, the Russians established the borders of their country close to modern ones, and explored almost the whole of Siberia, except the eastern Kamchatka and some regions north of the Arctic Circle.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] The conquest of Kamchatka later would be achieved in the early 1700s by Vladimir Atlasov, while the discovery of the Arctic coastline and Alaska would be completed by the Great Northern Expedition in 1733–1743.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] European overseas expansion led to contact between the Old and New Worlds producing the Columbian exchange.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] It started the global silver trade between the Americas, Europe, and China, and led to direct European involvement in the Chinese porcelain trade.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] It involved the transfer of goods unique from one hemisphere to another.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] From the Old World, Europeans brought cattle, horses, and sheep to the New World, and from the New World Europeans received tobacco, potatoes, tomatoes, and maize.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Other items and commodities becoming important in global trade were the tobacco, sugarcane, and cotton crops of the Americas, along with the gold and silver brought from the American continent not only to Europe, but elsewhere in the Old World.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] The formation of new transoceanic links and expansion of European influence led to the Age of Imperialism, which began during the Age of Discovery, during which colonial powers from Europe colonized most territory on the planet.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Combined with the introduction of infectious diseases from Europe, these events led to a drastic decrease of the American Indian population.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] American Indian accounts of European colonization were summarized by scholar Peter Mancall: "The arrival of Europeans brought death, displacement, sorrow, and despair to Native Americans".
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] In some areas, like North America, Central America, Australia, New Zealand, and Argentina, indigenous peoples were poorly treated, driven off their lands, and reduced to dependent minorities in the territory.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Similarly, in East and West Africa, local states supplied the appetite of European slave traders, changing the complexion of coastal African states and fundamentally altering the nature of slavery in Africa, causing impacts on societies and economies deep inland.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] In North America, there were many conflicts between European colonists and American Indians.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Maize and manioc were introduced into Africa in the 16th century by the Portuguese.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] They are now important staple foods, replacing native African crops.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Crosby speculated that increased production of maize, manioc, and other New World crops led to heavier concentrations of population in the areas from which slavers captured their victims.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] In the global silver trade, China was stimulated by trade with the Portuguese, Spaniards, and Dutch.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Although global, much of that silver ended up with the Chinese, and China dominated silver imports.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Between 1600 and 1800, China received 100 tons of silver on average per year.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] A large populace near the Lower Yangtze averaged hundreds of taels of silver per household in the late 16th century.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] More than 150,000 tons of silver were shipped from Potosí by the end of the 18th century.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] From 1500 to 1800, Mexico and Peru produced about 80% of the world's silver, with more than 30% of it eventually ending up in China (largely because European merchants used it to purchase exotic Chinese commodities).
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] In the late 16th and early 17th century, Japan was exporting heavily into China and foreign trade at large.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Trade with European powers and the Japanese brought in significant amounts of silver, which then replaced copper and paper banknotes as the common medium of exchange in China.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] During the last decades of the Ming dynasty, the flow of silver into China was greatly diminished, thereby undermining state revenues and the entire Ming economy.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] This damage to the economy was compounded by the effects on agriculture of the incipient Little Ice Age, natural calamities, crop failure, and sudden epidemics.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] The ensuing breakdown of authority and people's livelihoods allowed rebel leaders such as Li Zicheng to challenge Ming authority.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] New crops that had come to Asia from the Americas, via the Spanish colonizers in the 16th century, contributed to Asia's population growth.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Although the bulk of imports to China were silver, the Chinese also purchased New World crops from the Spanish Empire.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] This included sweet potatoes, maize, and peanuts, foods that could be cultivated in lands where traditional Chinese staple crops—wheat, millet, and rice—could not grow, hence facilitating a rise in the population of China.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] In the Song dynasty (960–1279), rice had become the major staple crop of the poor; after sweet potatoes were introduced to China around 1560, it gradually became the traditional food of the lower classes.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] The arrival of the Portuguese to Japan in 1543 initiated the Nanban trade period, with the Japanese adopting technologies and cultural practices, like the arquebus, European-style cuirasses, European ships, Christianity, decorative art, and language.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] After the Chinese had banned direct trade by Chinese merchants with Japan, the Portuguese filled this commercial vacuum as intermediaries.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] The Portuguese bought Chinese silk and sold it to the Japanese in return for Japanese-mined silver; since silver was more highly valued in China, the Portuguese could then use Japanese silver to buy even larger stocks of Chinese silk.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] By 1573, after the Spaniards established a trading base in Manila, the Portuguese intermediary trade was trumped by the prime source of incoming silver to China from the Spanish Americas.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Although China acted as the cog running the wheel of global trade during the 16th to 18th centuries, Japan's huge contribution of silver exports to China was critical to the world economy and China's liquidity and success with the commodity.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] As a wider variety of global luxury commodities entered the European markets by sea, previous European markets for luxury goods stagnated.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] The Atlantic trade largely supplanted pre-existing Italian and German trading powers which had relied on their Baltic, Russian, and Islamic trade links.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] The new commodities also caused social change, as sugar, spices, silks, and chinawares entered the luxury markets of Europe.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] The European economic centre shifted from the Mediterranean to Western Europe.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] The city of Antwerp, part of the Duchy of Brabant, became "the centre of the *entire* international economy", and the richest city in Europe.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Centred in Antwerp first and then Amsterdam, the Dutch Golden Age was tightly linked to the Age of Discovery.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] By 1549, the Portuguese empire sent annual trade missions to Shangchuan Island in China.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1557, they managed to convince the Ming court to agree on a legal port treaty that would establish Macau as an official Portuguese trade colony.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] From China, the major exports were silk and porcelain, adapted to meet European tastes.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] The Chinese export porcelains were held in such great esteem in Europe that, in English, *china* became a commonly used synonym for *porcelain*.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Kraak porcelain was among the first Chinese ware to arrive in Europe in significant quantities; only the richest could afford these early imports.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Soon the Dutch East India Company established trade with the East, having imported 6 million porcelain items from China to Europe between 1602 and 1682.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Kraak, mainly the blue and white porcelain, was imitated all over the world by potters in Arita, Japan and Persia—where Dutch merchants turned when the fall of the Ming dynasty rendered Chinese originals unavailable—and ultimately in delftware.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Dutch and later English delftware inspired by Chinese designs persisted from about 1630 to the mid-18th century alongside European patterns.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Antonio de Morga (1559–1636), a Spanish official in Manila, listed an extensive inventory of goods that were traded by Ming China at the turn of the 16th to 17th century, noting there were "rarities which, did I refer to them all, I would never finish, nor have sufficient paper for it".
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Ebrey writes of the considerable size of commercial transactions: In one case a galleon to the Spanish territories in the New World carried over 50,000 pairs of silk stockings.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] In return China imported mostly silver from Peruvian and Mexican mines, transported via Manila.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Chinese merchants were active in these trading ventures, and many emigrated to such places as the Philippines and Borneo to take advantage of the new commercial opportunities.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] The increase in gold and silver experienced by Spain coincided with a major inflationary cycle within Spain and Europe, known as the price revolution.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Spain had amassed large quantities of gold and silver from the New World.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] In the 1540s, large scale extraction of silver from Mexico began.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] During the 16th century, Spain held the equivalent of US$1.5 trillion (1990 terms) in gold and silver from New Spain.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Being the most powerful European monarch at a time full of war and religious conflicts, the Habsburg rulers spent their wealth in wars and arts across Europe.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] The spent silver, spread throughout a cash-starved Europe, caused widespread inflation.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] The inflation was worsened by a growing population with a static production level, low salaries and a rising cost of living, which damaged local industry.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Increasingly, Spain became dependent on the revenues flowing in from the mercantile empire, leading to Spain's first bankruptcy in 1557 due to rising military costs.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Philip II of Spain defaulted on debt payments in 1557, 1560, 1575, and 1596.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] The increase in prices as a result of currency circulation fuelled the growth of the commercial middle class in Europe, the *bourgeoisie*, which came to influence the politics and culture of many countries.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] One effect of the inflation, particularly in Great Britain, was that tenant farmers who held long-term leases from lords saw real decreases in rent.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-discovery-p03] Some lords opted to sell their leased land, giving rise to small, landowning farmers.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] The **Age of Sail** is the period in European history from the mid-15th or 16th century to, at the latest, the mid-19th century, in which the dominance of sailing ships in global trade and warfare culminated.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] Marked by the introduction of naval artillery, the Age of Sail ultimately reached its highest extent at the advent of steam power.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] Enabled by the advances of the related age of navigation, it is identified as a distinctive element of the early modern period and the Age of Discovery.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] Like most periodic eras, defining the age is inexact and serves only as a general description.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] The term is used differently for warships and merchant vessels.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] By the 14th century naval artillery was employed in Europe, documented at the Battle of Arnemuiden (1338).
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] The 15th century saw the Iberian naval ventures all the way along the African Atlantic coast and across the Atlantic Ocean, starting the Age of Discovery.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] For warships, the age of sail runs roughly from the Battle of Lepanto in 1571, the last significant engagement in which oar-propelled galleys played a major role, to the development of steam-powered warships.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] The period between the mid-19th century to the early 20th century, when sailing vessels reached their peak of size and complexity (e.g. clippers and windjammers), is sometimes referred to as the "Golden Age of Sail".
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] The second sea-going steamboat was Richard Wright's first steamboat *Experiment*, an ex-French lugger; she steamed from Leeds to Yarmouth in July 1813.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] The first iron steamship to go to sea was the 116-ton *Aaron Manby*, built in 1821 by Aaron Manby at the Horseley Ironworks, and became the first iron-built vessel to put to sea when she crossed the English Channel in 1822, arriving in Paris on 22 June.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] She carried passengers and freight to Paris in 1822 at an average speed of 8 knots (9.2 mph; 15 km/h).
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] The first purpose-built steam battleship was the 90-gun *Napoléon* in 1850.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] Multiple steam battleships saw action during the Crimean War, especially the Allied (British, French and Ottoman) fleet Bombardment of Sevastopol as part of the Siege of Sevastopol (1854–1855).
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] The first ironclad battleship, *Gloire*, was launched by the French Navy in November 1859.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] In the March 1862 Battle of Hampton Roads, the ironclad CSS *Virginia* fought USS *Monitor*, making this the first fight between ironclads.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] The Suez Canal in the Middle East, which opened in 1869, was more practical for steamships than for sailing ships, achieving a much shorter European-Asian sea route, which coincided with more fuel-efficient steamships, starting with *Agamemnon* in 1865.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] HMS *Devastation*, the first class of ocean-going battleships that did not carry sails, was commissioned in 1871.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] Sailing ships continued to be an economical way to transport bulk cargo on long voyages into the 1920s and 1930s, though steamships soon pushed them out of those trades as well.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] Sailing ships do not require fuel or complex engines to be powered; thus they tended to be more independent from sophisticated dedicated support bases on land.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] Crucially though, steam-powered ships held a speed advantage and were rarely hindered by adverse winds, freeing steam-powered vessels from the necessity of following trade winds.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] As a result, cargo and supplies could reach a foreign port in a fraction of the time it took a sailing ship.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] Sailing vessels were pushed into narrower and narrower economic niches and gradually disappeared from commercial trade.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] Today, sailing vessels are only economically viable for small-scale coastal fishing, along with recreational uses such as yachting and passenger sail excursion ships.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] In recent decades, the commercial shipping industry has been reviving interest in wind assisted ships as a way to conserve fuel in the interest of sustainability.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] A **New Age of Sail** has been predicted by some experts to occur by 2030, driven by a revolution in energy technology and a desire to reduce carbon emissions from maritime shipping through wind-assisted propulsion.
[src:baltimore-clipper/age-of-sail] The book *Trade Winds: A Voyage to a Sustainable Future for Shipping* discusses the potential of a return to wind propulsion through the firsthand experiences of Christiaan De Beukelaer, who spent five months aboard a sailing cargo ship in 2020.
[src:baltimore-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Captain **Alfred Bulltop Stormalong** was an American folk hero and the subject of numerous nautical-themed tall tales originating in Massachusetts.
[src:baltimore-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Stormalong was said to be a sailor and a giant, some 30 feet (9.1 m) tall; he was the master of a huge clipper ship known in various sources as either the *Courser* or the *Tuscarora*, a ship purportedly so tall that it had hinged masts to avoid catching on the Moon.
[src:baltimore-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The name of Stormalong first appeared in a cycle of sea shanties that Stan Hugill, in his *Sea Shanties of the Seven Seas*, traces back to African-American folk songs of the 1830s and '40s.
[src:baltimore-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Bearing names like "Mister Stormalong", "Way Stormalong John", and "Yankee John, Stormalong", these sailors' work songs generally featured praise for a deceased seaman and for his benevolent son.
[src:baltimore-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The tall tales about Stormalong first appeared in the 1911 book *Here's Audacity!* by Frank Shay.
[src:baltimore-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] More tales appeared in the 1933 pamphlet *Old Stormalong Yarns* by C.E.
[src:baltimore-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] New England was where he was beached as a baby, already three fathoms (18 ft) tall.
[src:baltimore-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] According to one telling, he outgrew Cape Cod and moved to Boston, where he signed aboard the first ship that would take him at the age of twelve.
[src:baltimore-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] He had a lifelong rivalry with a Kraken, a huge sea monster from Norse myth; in fact, the Kraken escaped from him in their first encounter, causing a dejected Stormalong to abandon the sea life for life as a farmer somewhere in the Midwest.
[src:baltimore-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Some sources say he had a ship so large that a stable of Arabian horses were aboard for his crew to get from one end of the ship to the other.
[src:baltimore-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Among other things, the ship Alfred was best said to have drilled the course of the Panama Canal by slamming into the Panamanian coast, and to have gotten stuck in the English Channel, which required the crew to grease the ship's hull with soap.
[src:baltimore-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The soap combined with the scraping of the hull against the Gray Cliffs of Dover turned them bright white.
[src:baltimore-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] As Stormalong grew older, he eventually encountered the Kraken again, this time successfully drawing the beast into a whirlpool from which it never escaped.
[src:baltimore-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The aged Stormalong won the race by several miles, but the stress of handling the wheel through the difficult Atlantic crossing killed him.
[src:baltimore-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Stormalong was buried at sea, and Davy Jones himself opened his famous locker to accept Stormalong's body.
[src:baltimore-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Another ending to his life is as follows: While Stormalong was on his Caribbean adventures, he passed by Florida, seeing that there was a tremendous hurricane that tore through his ship.
[src:baltimore-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Ships sailing nearby were being tossed around by the heavy waves.
[src:baltimore-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Stormalong went overboard and piled as many boats as he could onto his ship.
[src:baltimore-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] When the storm finally wound down, the sailors were dropped back off at Florida.
[src:baltimore-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] After that, he went back on board, unfurling the sails of his ship, seeing if they could be repaired.
[src:baltimore-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] A great wind, the last blow of the hurricane, hit the sails, lifting Stormalong and his ship into the sky.
[src:baltimore-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] A third ending to his life takes advantage of the inference that, being a giant, Alfred Bulltop Stormalong was an enormous eater.
[src:baltimore-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] It describes a time when his hunger was greater than usual and led him to eat so much food (one variant cites a breakfast of six sharks; it is not definitely known what other variants exist) that he suffered terminal indigestion, causing his magnificent appetite to finish him.
[src:baltimore-clipper/ambassador-clipper] William Walker built *Ambassador* at Lavender Dry Dock in London.
[src:baltimore-clipper/ambassador-clipper] Though considered a fast ship, *Ambassador* was said to be "very cranky and overmasted".
[src:baltimore-clipper/ambassador-clipper] Her first passage to the UK from Fuzhou came during the Tea Race of 1870 under Captain Duggan and took 115 days, a mediocre performance; that same year the fastest tea passage, also from Fuzhou, was made by the clipper *Lahloo* in just 98 days.
[src:baltimore-clipper/ambassador-clipper] *Ambassador*'s fastest passage between China and England was 108 days, in 1872.
[src:baltimore-clipper/ambassador-clipper] The wreck is now reduced to a skeletal frame.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The conflict was fought in North America, the Caribbean, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The war's outcome seemed uncertain for most of the war, but Washington and the Continental Army's decisive victory in the Siege of Yorktown in 1781 led King George III and the Kingdom of Great Britain to negotiate an end to the war.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In 1783, in the Treaty of Paris, the British monarchy acknowledged the independence of the Thirteen Colonies, leading to the establishment of the United States as an independent and sovereign nation.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In 1763, after the British Empire gained dominance in North America following its victory over the French in the Seven Years' War, tensions and disputes began escalating between the British and the Thirteen Colonies, especially following passage of the Stamp and Townshend Acts.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The British Army responded by seeking to occupy Boston militarily, leading to the Boston Massacre on March 5, 1770.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In mid-1774, with tensions escalating even further between the British Army and the colonies, the British Parliament imposed the Intolerable Acts, an attempt to disarm Americans, leading to the Battles of Lexington and Concord in April 1775, the first battles of the Revolutionary War.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In June 1775, the Second Continental Congress voted to incorporate colonial-based Patriot militias into a central military, the Continental Army, and unanimously appointed Washington its commander-in-chief.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Two months later, in August 1775, George III declared the colonies to be in a state of rebellion.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In July 1776, the Second Continental Congress formalized the war, passing the Lee Resolution on July 2, and, two days later, unanimously adopting the Declaration of Independence, on July 4.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In March 1776, in an early win for the newly-formed Continental Army under Washington's command, following a successful siege of Boston, the Continental Army successfully drove the British Army out of Boston.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] British commander in chief William Howe responded by launching the New York and New Jersey campaign, which resulted in Howe's capture of New York City in November.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Washington responded by clandestinely crossing the Delaware River and winning small but significant victories at Trenton and Princeton.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In the summer of 1777, as Howe was poised to capture Philadelphia, the Continental Congress fled to Baltimore.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In October 1777, a separate northern British force under the command of John Burgoyne was forced to surrender at Saratoga in an American victory that proved crucial in convincing France and Spain that an independent United States was a viable possibility.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] France signed a commercial agreement with the revolutionaires, followed by a Treaty of Alliance in February 1778.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In 1779, the Sullivan Expedition undertook a scorched earth campaign against British-allied factions of the Haudenosaunee Confederacy (*also* Iroquois).
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Native American raids on the American frontier, however, continued to be a problem.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Also, in 1779, Spain allied with France against Great Britain in the Treaty of Aranjuez, though Spain did not formally ally with the Americans.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Howe's replacement Henry Clinton intended to take the war against the Americans into the Southern Colonies.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Despite some initial success, British General Cornwallis was besieged by a Franco-American army in Yorktown, Virginia, in September and October 1781.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The French navy cut off Cornwallis's escape and he was forced to surrender in October.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The British wars with France and Spain continued for another two years, but fighting largely ceased in North America.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In the Treaty of Paris, signed on September 3, 1783, Great Britain acknowledged the sovereignty and independence of the United States, bringing the American Revolutionary War to an end.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The Treaties of Versailles resolved Great Britain's conflicts with France and Spain, and forced Great Britain to cede Tobago, Senegal, and small territories in India to France, and Menorca, West Florida, and East Florida to Spain.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The French and Indian War, part of the wider global conflict known as the Seven Years' War, ended with the 1763 Peace of Paris, which expelled France from their possessions in New France.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The Royal Proclamation of 1763 was designed to refocus colonial expansion north into Nova Scotia and south into Florida, with the Mississippi River as the dividing line between British and Spanish possessions in America.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Settlement was tightly restricted beyond the 1763 limits, and claims west of this line, including by Virginia and Massachusetts, were rescinded.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] With the exception of Virginia and others deprived of rights to western lands, the colonial legislatures agreed on the boundaries but disagreed on where to set them.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Many settlers resented the restrictions entirely, and enforcement required permanent garrisons along the frontier, which led to increasingly bitter disputes over who should pay for them.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The huge debt incurred by the Seven Years' War and demands from British taxpayers for cuts in government expenditure meant Parliament expected the colonies to fund their own defense.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The 1763 to 1765 Grenville ministry instructed the Royal Navy to cease trading smuggled goods and enforce customs duties levied in American ports.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The most important was the 1733 Molasses Act; routinely ignored before 1763, it had a significant economic impact since 85% of New England rum exports were manufactured from imported molasses.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] These measures were followed by the Sugar Act and Stamp Act, which imposed additional taxes on the colonies to pay for defending the western frontier.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The taxes proved highly burdensome, particularly for the poorer classes, and quickly became a source of discontent.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In July 1765, the Whigs formed the First Rockingham ministry, which repealed the Stamp Act and reduced tax on foreign molasses to help the New England economy, but re-asserted Parliamentary authority in the Declaratory Act.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] However, this did little to end the discontent; in 1768, a riot started in Boston when the authorities seized the sloop *Liberty* on suspicion of smuggling.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Tensions escalated in March 1770 when British troops fired on rock-throwing civilians, killing five in what became known as the Boston Massacre.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The Massacre coincided with the partial repeal of the Townshend Acts by the Tory-based North Ministry.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] North insisted on retaining duty on tea to enshrine Parliament's right to tax the colonies; the amount was minor, but ignored the fact it was that very principle Americans found objectionable.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In April 1772, colonialists staged the first American tax revolt against British royal authority in Weare, New Hampshire, later referred to as the Pine Tree Riot.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] This would inspire the design of the Pine Tree Flag.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Tensions escalated following the destruction of a customs vessel in the June 1772 Gaspee Affair, then came to a head in 1773.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] A banking crisis led to the near-collapse of the East India Company, which dominated the British economy; to support it, Parliament passed the Tea Act, giving it a trading monopoly in the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Since most American tea was smuggled by the Dutch, the act was opposed by those who managed the illegal trade, while being seen as another attempt to impose the principle of taxation by Parliament.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In December 1773, a group called the Sons of Liberty disguised as Mohawks dumped crates of tea into Boston Harbor, an event later known as the Boston Tea Party.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The British Parliament responded by passing the so-called Intolerable Acts, aimed specifically at Massachusetts, although many colonists and members of the Whig opposition considered them a threat to liberty in general.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] This increased sympathy for the Patriot cause locally, in the British Parliament, and in the London press.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Throughout the 18th century, the elected lower houses in the colonial legislatures gradually wrested power from their governors.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Dominated by smaller landowners and merchants, these assemblies now established ad-hoc provincial legislatures, effectively replacing royal control.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] With the exception of Georgia, twelve colonies sent representatives to the First Continental Congress to agree on a unified response to the crisis.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Many of the delegates feared that a boycott would result in war and sent a Petition to the King calling for the repeal of the Intolerable Acts.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] After some debate, on September 17, 1774, Congress endorsed the Massachusetts Suffolk Resolves and on October 20 passed the Continental Association, which instituted economic sanctions and a boycott of goods against Britain.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] While denying its authority over internal American affairs, a faction led by James Duane and future Loyalist Joseph Galloway insisted Congress recognize Parliament's right to regulate colonial trade.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Expecting concessions by the North administration, Congress authorized the colonial legislatures to enforce the boycott; this succeeded in reducing British imports by 97% from 1774 to 1775.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] However, on February 9 Parliament declared Massachusetts to be in rebellion and instituted a blockade of the colony.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] In July, the Restraining Acts limited colonial trade with the British West Indies and Britain and barred New England ships from the Newfoundland cod fisheries.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The tension led to a scramble for control of militia stores, which each assembly was legally obliged to maintain for defense.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] On April 19, a British attempt to secure the Concord arsenal culminated in the Battles of Lexington and Concord, which began the Revolutionary War.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] After the Patriot victory at Concord, moderates in Congress led by John Dickinson drafted the Olive Branch Petition, offering to accept royal authority in return for George III mediating in the dispute.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] However, since the petition was immediately followed by the Declaration of the Causes and Necessity of Taking Up Arms, Colonial Secretary Lord Dartmouth viewed the offer as insincere and refused to present the petition to the king.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Although constitutionally correct, since the monarch could not oppose his own government, it disappointed those Americans who hoped he would mediate in the dispute, while the hostility of his language annoyed even Loyalist members of Congress.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Combined with the Proclamation of Rebellion, issued on August 23 in response to the Battle at Bunker Hill, it ended hopes of a peaceful settlement.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Backed by the Whigs, Parliament initially rejected the imposition of coercive measures by 170 votes, fearing an aggressive policy would drive the Americans towards independence.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] However, by the end of 1774 the collapse of British authority meant both Lord North and George III were convinced war was inevitable.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] After Boston, Gage halted operations and awaited reinforcements; the Irish Parliament approved the recruitment of new regiments, while allowing Catholics to enlist for the first time.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Britain also signed a series of treaties with German states to supply additional troops.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Within a year, it had an army of over 32,000 men in America, the largest ever sent outside Europe at the time.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The employment of German soldiers against people viewed as British citizens was opposed by many in Parliament and by the colonial assemblies; combined with the lack of activity by Gage, opposition to the use of foreign troops allowed the Patriots to take control of the legislatures.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Support for independence was boosted by Thomas Paine's pamphlet *Common Sense*, which was published on January 10, 1776, and argued for American self-government and was widely reprinted.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] To draft the Declaration of Independence, the Second Continental Congress appointed the Committee of Five: Thomas Jefferson, John Adams, Benjamin Franklin, Roger Sherman, and Robert Livingston.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The declaration was written almost exclusively by Jefferson.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Identifying inhabitants of the Thirteen Colonies as "one people", the declaration simultaneously dissolved political links with Britain, while including a long list of alleged violations of "English rights" committed by George III.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] This is also one of the first times that the colonies were referred to as "United States", rather than the more common United Colonies.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] On July 2, Congress voted for independence and published the declaration on July 4.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] At this point, the revolution ceased to be an internal dispute over trade and tax policies between the Thirteen Colonies and Great Britain, becoming a civil war, with each state represented in Congress engaged in a struggle with Britain.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The conflict was also a civil war between American Patriots and American Loyalists.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Patriots generally supported independence from Britain and a new national union in Congress, while Loyalists remained aligned with British rule.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Estimates of numbers vary, one suggestion being the population as a whole was split evenly between committed Patriots, committed Loyalists, and those who were indifferent.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Others calculate the split as 40% Patriot, 40% neutral, 20% Loyalist, but with considerable regional variations.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] At the onset of the war, the Second Continental Congress realized defeating Britain required foreign alliances and intelligence-gathering.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] The Committee of Secret Correspondence was formed for "the sole purpose of corresponding with our friends in Great Britain and other parts of the world".
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] From 1775 to 1776, the committee shared information and built alliances through secret correspondence, as well as employing secret agents in Europe to gather intelligence, conduct undercover operations, analyze foreign publications, and initiate Patriot propaganda campaigns.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p01] Paine served as secretary, while Benjamin Franklin and Silas Deane, sent to France, Britain's longtime rival, to recruit military engineers, were instrumental in securing French aid in Paris.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On April 14, 1775, Sir Thomas Gage, Commander-in-Chief, North America and Governor of Massachusetts, received orders to take action against the Patriots.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] He decided to destroy militia ordnance stored at Concord, Massachusetts, and capture John Hancock and Samuel Adams, who were considered the principal instigators of the rebellion.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The operation was to begin around midnight on April 19, in the hope of completing it before the American Patriots could respond.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] However, Paul Revere learned of the plan and notified Captain Parker, commander of the Concord militia, who prepared to resist.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The first action of the war, commonly referred to as the shot heard round the world, was a brief skirmish at Lexington, followed by the full-scale Battles of Lexington and Concord.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] British troops suffered around 300 casualties before withdrawing to Boston, which was then besieged by the militia.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In May 1775, 4,500 British reinforcements arrived under Generals William Howe, John Burgoyne, and Sir Henry Clinton.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On June 17, they seized the Charlestown Peninsula at the Battle of Bunker Hill, a frontal assault in which they suffered over 1,000 casualties.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Dismayed at the costly attack which had gained them little, Gage appealed to London for a larger army, but instead was replaced as commander by Howe.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On June 14, 1775, Congress took control of Patriot forces outside Boston, and Congressional leader John Adams nominated Washington as commander-in-chief of the newly formed Continental Army.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On June 16, Hancock officially proclaimed him "General and Commander in Chief of the army of the United Colonies." He assumed command on July 3, preferring to fortify Dorchester Heights outside Boston rather than assaulting it.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In early March 1776, Colonel Henry Knox arrived with heavy artillery acquired in the Capture of Fort Ticonderoga.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Under cover of darkness, on March 5, Washington placed these on Dorchester Heights, from where they could fire on the town and British ships in Boston Harbor.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Fearing another Bunker Hill, Howe evacuated the city on March 17 without further loss and sailed to Halifax, Nova Scotia, while Washington moved south to New York City.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Beginning in August 1775, American privateers raided towns in Nova Scotia, including Saint John, Charlottetown, and Yarmouth.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In 1776, John Paul Jones and Jonathan Eddy attacked Canso and Fort Cumberland respectively.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] British officials in Quebec began negotiating with the Iroquois for their support, while US envoys urged them to remain neutral.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Aware of Native American leanings toward the British and fearing an Anglo-Indian attack from Canada, Congress authorized a second invasion in April 1775.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] After the defeat at the Battle of Quebec on December 31, the Americans maintained a loose blockade of the city until they retreated on May 6, 1776.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A second defeat at Trois-Rivières on June 8 ended operations in Quebec.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] British pursuit was initially blocked by American naval vessels on Lake Champlain until victory at Valcour Island on October 11 forced the Americans to withdraw to Fort Ticonderoga, while in December an uprising in Nova Scotia sponsored by Massachusetts was defeated at Fort Cumberland.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] These failures impacted public support for the Patriot cause, and aggressive anti-Loyalist policies in the New England colonies alienated the Canadians.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In Virginia, Dunmore's Proclamation on November 7, 1775, promised freedom to any slaves who fled their Patriot masters and agreed to fight for the Crown.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] British forces were defeated at Great Bridge on December 9 and took refuge on British ships anchored near Norfolk.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] When the Third Virginia Convention refused to disband its militia or accept martial law, Lord Dunmore ordered the Burning of Norfolk on January 1, 1776.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The siege of Savage's Old Fields began on November 19 in South Carolina between Loyalist and Patriot militias, and the Loyalists were subsequently driven out of the colony in the Snow Campaign.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Loyalists were recruited in North Carolina to reassert British rule in the South, but they were decisively defeated in the Battle of Moore's Creek Bridge.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A British expedition sent to reconquer South Carolina launched an attack on Charleston in the Battle of Sullivan's Island on June 28, 1776, but it failed.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A shortage of gunpowder led Congress to authorize a naval expedition against the Bahamas to secure ordnance stored there.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On March 3, 1776, an American squadron under the command of Esek Hopkins landed at the east end of Nassau and encountered minimal resistance at Fort Montagu.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Hopkins' troops then marched on Fort Nassau.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Hopkins had promised governor Montfort Browne and the civilian inhabitants that their lives and property would not be in any danger if they offered no resistance; they complied.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Hopkins captured large stores of powder and other munitions that was so great he had to impress an extra ship in the harbor to transport the supplies back home, when he departed on March 17.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A month later, after a brief skirmish with HMS *Glasgow*, they returned to New London, Connecticut, the base for American naval operations.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] After regrouping at Halifax in Nova Scotia, Howe set sail for New York in June 1776 and began landing troops on Staten Island near the entrance to New York Harbor on July 2.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Americans rejected Howe's informal attempt to negotiate peace on July 30; Washington knew that an attack on the city was imminent and realized that he needed advance information to deal with disciplined British regular troops.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On August 12, 1776, Patriot Thomas Knowlton was ordered to form an elite group for reconnaissance and secret missions.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Knowlton's Rangers, which included Nathan Hale, became the Army's first intelligence unit.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] When Washington was driven off Long Island, he soon realized that he would need to professionalize military intelligence.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] With aid from Benjamin Tallmadge, Washington launched the six-man Culper spy ring.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The efforts of Washington and the Culper Spy Ring substantially increased the effective allocation and deployment of Continental regiments in the field.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Throughout the war, Washington spent more than 10 percent of his total military funds on military intelligence.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Washington split the Continental Army into positions on Manhattan and across the East River in western Long Island.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On August 27 at the Battle of Long Island, Howe outflanked Washington and forced him back to Brooklyn Heights, but he did not attempt to encircle Washington's forces.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Through the night of August 28, Knox bombarded the British.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Knowing they were up against overwhelming odds, Washington ordered the assembly of a war council on August 29; all agreed to retreat to Manhattan.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Washington quickly had his troops assembled and ferried them across the East River to Manhattan on flat-bottomed freight boats without any losses in men or ordnance, leaving General Thomas Mifflin's regiments as a rearguard.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Howe met with a delegation from the Second Continental Congress at the September Staten Island Peace Conference, but it failed to conclude peace, largely because the British delegates only had the authority to offer pardons and could not recognize independence.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On September 15, Howe seized control of New York City when the British landed at Kip's Bay and unsuccessfully engaged the Americans at the Battle of Harlem Heights the following day.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On October 18, Howe failed to encircle the Americans at the Battle of Pell's Point, and the Americans withdrew.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Howe declined to close with Washington's army on October 28 at the Battle of White Plains and instead attacked a hill that was of no strategic value.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Washington's retreat isolated his remaining forces and the British captured Fort Washington on November 16.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The British victory there amounted to Washington's most disastrous defeat with the loss of 3,000 prisoners.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The remaining American regiments on Long Island fell back four days later.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] General Henry Clinton wanted to pursue Washington's disorganized army, but he was first required to commit 6,000 troops to capture Newport, Rhode Island, to secure the Loyalist port.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] General Charles Cornwallis pursued Washington, but Howe ordered him to halt.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The outlook following the defeat at Fort Washington appeared bleak for the American cause.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The reduced Continental Army had dwindled to fewer than 5,000 men and was reduced further when enlistments expired at the end of the year.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Popular support wavered, and morale declined.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On December 20, 1776, the Continental Congress abandoned the revolutionary capital of Philadelphia and moved to Baltimore, where it remained until February 27, 1777.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Loyalist activity surged in the wake of the American defeat, especially in New York state.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In London, news of the victorious Long Island campaign was well received with festivities held in the capital.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Strategic deficiencies among Patriot forces were evident: Washington divided a numerically weaker army in the face of a stronger one, his inexperienced staff misread the military situation, and American troops fled in the face of enemy fire.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The successes led to predictions that the British could win within a year.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The British established winter quarters in the New York City area and anticipated renewed campaigning the following spring.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On the night of December 25–26, 1776, Washington crossed the Delaware River, leading a column of Continental Army troops from today's Bucks County, Pennsylvania, to today's Mercer County, New Jersey, in a logistically challenging and dangerous operation.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Meanwhile, the Hessians were involved in numerous clashes with small bands of Patriots and were often aroused by false alarms at night in the weeks before the actual Battle of Trenton.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] By Christmas they were tired, while a heavy snowstorm led their commander, Colonel Johann Rall, to assume no significant attack would occur.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] At daybreak on the 26th, the American Patriots surprised and overwhelmed Rall and his troops, who lost over 20 killed including Rall, while 900 prisoners, German cannons and supplies were captured.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Battle of Trenton restored the American army's morale, reinvigorated the Patriot cause, and dispelled their fear of what they regarded as Hessian "mercenaries".
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A British attempt to retake Trenton was repulsed at Assunpink Creek on January 2; during the night, Washington outmaneuvered Cornwallis, then defeated his rearguard in the Battle of Princeton the following day.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The two victories helped convince the French that the Americans were worthy military allies.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] After his success at Princeton, Washington entered winter quarters at Morristown, New Jersey, where he remained until May and received Congressional direction to inoculate all Patriot troops against smallpox.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] With the exception of a minor skirmishing between the two armies which continued until March, Howe made no attempt to attack the Americans.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The 1776 campaign demonstrated that regaining New England would be a prolonged affair, which led to a change in British strategy to isolating the north by taking control of the Hudson River, allowing them to focus on the south where Loyalist support was believed to be substantial.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In December 1776, Howe wrote to the Colonial Secretary Lord Germain, proposing a limited offensive against Philadelphia, while a second force moved down the Hudson from Canada.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Burgoyne supplied several alternatives, all of which gave him responsibility for the offensive, with Howe remaining on the defensive.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The option selected required him to lead the main force south from Montreal down the Hudson Valley, while a detachment under Barry St.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The two would meet at Albany, leaving Howe to decide whether to join them.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Reasonable in principle, this did not account for the logistical difficulties involved and Burgoyne erroneously assumed Howe would remain on the defensive; Germain's failure to make this clear meant he opted to attack Philadelphia instead.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] With a mixed force of British regulars, professional German soldiers and Canadian militia Burgoyne set out on June 14, 1777, and captured Fort Ticonderoga on July 5.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] As General Horatio Gates retreated, his troops blocked roads, destroyed bridges, dammed streams, and stripped the area of food.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This slowed Burgoyne's progress and forced him to send out large foraging expeditions; one of more than 700 British troops were captured at the Battle of Bennington on August 16.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] St Leger moved east and besieged Fort Stanwix; despite defeating an American relief force at the Battle of Oriskany on August 6, St.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Leger was abandoned by his Indian allies and withdrew to Quebec on August 22.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Now isolated and outnumbered by Gates, Burgoyne continued onto Albany rather than retreating to Fort Ticonderoga, reaching Saratoga on September 13.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] He asked Clinton for support while constructing defenses around the town.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Morale among his troops rapidly declined, and an unsuccessful attempt to break past Gates at the Battle of Freeman Farms on September 19 resulted in 600 British casualties.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] When Clinton advised he could not reach them, Burgoyne's subordinates advised retreat; a reconnaissance in force on October 7 was repulsed by Gates at the Battle of Bemis Heights, forcing them back into Saratoga with heavy losses.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] By October 11, all hope of British escape had vanished; persistent rain reduced the camp to a "squalid hell" and supplies were dangerously low.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Burgoyne capitulated on October 17; around 6,222 soldiers, including German forces commanded by General Friedrich Adolf Riedesel, surrendered their arms before being taken to Boston, where they were to be transported to England.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] After securing additional supplies, Howe made another attempt on Philadelphia by landing his troops in Chesapeake Bay on August 24.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] He now compounded failure to support Burgoyne by missing repeated opportunities to destroy his opponent: despite defeating Washington at the Battle of Brandywine on September 11, he then allowed him to withdraw in good order.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] After dispersing an American detachment at Paoli on September 20, Cornwallis occupied Philadelphia on September 26, with the main force of 9,000 under Howe based just to the north at Germantown.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Washington attacked them on October 4, but was repulsed.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] To prevent Howe's forces in Philadelphia being resupplied by sea, the Patriots erected Fort Mifflin and nearby Fort Mercer on the east and west banks of the Delaware respectively, and placed obstacles in the river south of the city.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This was supported by a small flotilla of Continental Navy ships on the Delaware, supplemented by the Pennsylvania State Navy, commanded by John Hazelwood.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] An attempt by the Royal Navy to take the forts in the October 20 to 22 Battle of Red Bank failed; a second attack captured Fort Mifflin on November 16, while Fort Mercer was abandoned two days later when Cornwallis breached the walls.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] His supply lines secured, Howe tried to tempt Washington into giving battle, but after inconclusive skirmishing at the Battle of White Marsh from December 5 to 8, he withdrew to Philadelphia for the winter.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On December 19, the Americans followed suit and entered winter quarters at Valley Forge.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] As Washington's domestic opponents contrasted his lack of battlefield success with Gates' victory at Saratoga, foreign observers such as Frederick the Great were equally impressed with Washington's command at Germantown, which demonstrated resilience and determination.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Over the winter, poor conditions, supply problems and low morale resulted in 2,000 deaths, with another 3,000 unfit for duty due to lack of shoes.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] However, Baron Friedrich Wilhelm von Steuben took the opportunity to introduce Prussian Army drill and infantry tactics to "model companies" in each Continental Army regiment, who then instructed their home units.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Despite Valley Forge being only twenty miles away, Howe made no effort to attack their camp, an action some critics argue could have ended the war.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Like his predecessors, French foreign minister Vergennes considered the 1763 Peace a national humiliation and viewed the war as an opportunity to weaken Britain.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] He initially avoided open conflict, but allowed American ships to take on cargoes in French ports, a technical violation of neutrality.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Vergennes persuaded Louis XVI to secretly fund a government front company to purchase munitions for the Patriots, carried in neutral Dutch ships and imported through Sint Eustatius in the Caribbean.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Many Americans opposed a French alliance, fearing to "exchange one tyranny for another", but this changed after a series of military setbacks in early 1776.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] As France had nothing to gain from the colonies reconciling with Britain, Congress had three choices: making peace on British terms, continuing the struggle on their own, or proclaiming independence, guaranteed by France.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Although the Declaration of Independence had wide public support, over 20% of Congressmen voted against an alliance with France.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Congress agreed to the treaty with reluctance and as the war moved in their favor increasingly lost interest in it.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Silas Deane was sent to Paris to begin negotiations with Vergennes, whose key objectives were replacing Britain as the United States' primary commercial and military partner while securing the French West Indies from American expansion.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] These islands were extremely valuable; in 1772, the value of sugar and coffee produced by Saint-Domingue on its own exceeded that of all American exports combined.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Talks progressed slowly until October 1777, when British defeat at Saratoga and their apparent willingness to negotiate peace convinced Vergennes only a permanent alliance could prevent the "disaster" of Anglo-American rapprochement.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Assurances of formal French support allowed Congress to reject the Carlisle Peace Commission and insist on nothing short of complete independence.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On February 6, 1778, France and the United States signed the Treaty of Amity and Commerce regulating trade between the two countries, followed by a defensive military alliance against Britain, the Treaty of Alliance.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In return for French guarantees of American independence, Congress undertook to defend their interests in the West Indies, while both sides agreed not to make a separate peace; conflict over these provisions would lead to the 1798 to 1800 Quasi-War.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Charles III of Spain was invited to join on the same terms but refused, largely due to concerns over the impact of the Revolution on Spanish colonies in the Americas.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Spain had complained on multiple occasions about encroachment by American settlers into Louisiana, a problem that could only get worse once the United States replaced Britain.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Although Spain ultimately made important contributions to American success, in the Treaty of Aranjuez, Charles agreed only to support France's war with Britain outside America, in return for help in recovering Gibraltar, Menorca and Spanish Florida.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The terms were confidential since several conflicted with American aims; for example, the French claimed exclusive control of the Newfoundland cod fisheries, a non-negotiable for colonies like Massachusetts.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] One less well-known impact of this agreement was the abiding American distrust of 'foreign entanglements'; the US would not sign another treaty with France until their NATO agreement of 1949.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This was because the US had agreed not to make peace without France, while Aranjuez committed France to keep fighting until Spain recovered Gibraltar, effectively making it a condition of US independence without the knowledge of Congress.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] To encourage French participation in the struggle for independence, the US representative in Paris, Silas Deane, promised promotion and command positions to any French officer who joined the Continental Army.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This included Gilbert du Motier, Marquis de Lafayette, whom Congress via Dean appointed a major general, on July 31, 1777.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] When the war started, Britain tried to borrow the Dutch-based Scots Brigade for service in America, but pro-Patriot sentiment led the States General to refuse.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Although the Republic was no longer a major power, prior to 1774 they still dominated the European carrying trade, and Dutch merchants made large profits shipping French-supplied munitions to the Patriots.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This ended when Britain declared war in December 1780, a conflict that proved disastrous to the Dutch economy.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The British government failed to take into account the strength of the American merchant marine and support from European countries, which allowed the colonies to import munitions and continue trading with relative impunity.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] While well aware of this, the North administration delayed placing the Royal Navy on a war footing for cost reasons; this prevented the institution of an effective blockade.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Traditional British policy was to employ European land-based allies to divert the opposition; in 1778, they were diplomatically isolated and faced war on multiple fronts.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Meanwhile, George III had given up on subduing America while Britain had a European war to fight.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] He did not welcome war with France, but he held the British victories over France in the Seven Years' War as a reason to believe in ultimate victory over France.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Britain subsequently changed its focus into the Caribbean theater, and diverted major military resources away from America.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] At the end of 1777, Howe resigned and was replaced by Sir Henry Clinton on May 24, 1778; with French entry into the war, he was ordered to consolidate his forces in New York.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On June 18, the British departed Philadelphia with the reinvigorated Americans in pursuit; the Battle of Monmouth on June 28 was inconclusive but boosted Patriot morale.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] That midnight, the newly installed Clinton continued his retreat to New York.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A French naval force under Admiral Charles Henri Hector d'Estaing was sent to assist Washington; deciding New York was too formidable a target, in August they launched a combined attack on Newport, with General John Sullivan commanding land forces.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The resulting Battle of Rhode Island was indecisive; badly damaged by a storm, the French withdrew to avoid risking their ships.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Further activity was limited to British raids on Chestnut Neck and Little Egg Harbor in October.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In July 1779, the Americans captured British positions at Stony Point and Paulus Hook.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Clinton unsuccessfully tried to tempt Washington into a decisive engagement by sending General William Tryon to raid Connecticut.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In July, a large American naval operation, the Penobscot Expedition, attempted to retake Maine but was defeated.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Persistent raids by British-allied tribes in New York and Pennsylvania led to the punitive Sullivan Expedition from July to September 1779.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] However, 5,000 British-allied tribes of Iroquois fled to Canada where, supplied and supported by the British, they continued their raids.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] During the winter of 1779–1780, the Continental Army suffered greater hardships than at Valley Forge.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Morale was poor, public support fell away, the Continental dollar was virtually worthless, the army was plagued with supply problems, desertion was common, and mutinies occurred in the Pennsylvania Line and New Jersey Line regiments over the conditions.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In June 1780, Clinton sent 6,000 men under Wilhelm von Knyphausen to retake New Jersey, but they were halted by local militia at the Battle of Connecticut Farms; although the Americans withdrew, Knyphausen felt he was not strong enough to engage Washington's main force and retreated.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] A second attempt two weeks later ended in a British defeat at the Battle of Springfield, effectively ending their ambitions in New Jersey.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In July, Washington appointed Benedict Arnold commander of West Point; his attempt to betray the fort to the British failed due to incompetent planning, and the plot was revealed when his British contact John André was captured and executed.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Arnold escaped to New York and switched sides, an action justified in a pamphlet addressed "To the Inhabitants of America"; the Patriots condemned his betrayal, while he found himself almost as unpopular with the British.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Southern Strategy was developed by Lord Germain, based on input from London-based Loyalists, including Joseph Galloway.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] They argued that it made no sense to fight the Patriots in the north where they were strongest, while the New England economy was reliant on trade with Britain.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On the other hand, duties on tobacco made the South far more profitable for Britain, while local support meant securing it required small numbers of regular troops.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Victory would leave a truncated United States facing British possessions to the south, north, and west; with the Atlantic seaboard controlled by the Royal Navy, Congress would be forced to agree to terms.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] However, assumptions about the level of Loyalist support proved wildly optimistic.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Germain ordered Augustine Prevost, the British commander in East Florida, to advance into Georgia in December 1778.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Lieutenant-Colonel Archibald Campbell, an experienced officer, captured Savannah on December 29, 1778.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] He recruited a Loyalist militia of nearly 1,100, many of whom allegedly joined only after Campbell threatened to confiscate their property.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Poor motivation and training made them unreliable troops, as demonstrated in their defeat by Patriot militia at the Battle of Kettle Creek on February 14, 1779, although this was offset by British victory at Brier Creek on March 3.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In June 1779, Prevost launched an abortive assault on Charleston, before retreating to Savannah, an operation notorious for widespread looting by British troops that enraged both Loyalists and Patriots.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In October, a joint French and American operation under d'Estaing and General Benjamin Lincoln failed to recapture Savannah.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Prevost was replaced by Lord Cornwallis, who assumed responsibility for Germain's strategy; he soon realized estimates of Loyalist support were considerably over-stated, and he needed far more regular forces.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Reinforced by Clinton, Cornwallis's troops captured Charleston in May 1780, inflicting the most serious Patriot defeat of the war; over 5,000 prisoners were taken and the Continental Army in the south effectively destroyed.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On May 29, Lieutenant-Colonel Banastre Tarleton's mainly Loyalist force routed a Continental Army force nearly three times its size under Colonel Abraham Buford at the Battle of Waxhaws.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The battle is controversial for allegations of a massacre, which were later used as a recruiting tool by the Patriots.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Clinton returned to New York, leaving Cornwallis to oversee the south; despite their success, the two men left barely on speaking terms.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Southern strategy depended on local support, but this was undermined by a series of coercive measures.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Previously, captured Patriots were sent home after swearing not to take up arms against the king; they were now required to fight their former comrades, while the confiscation of Patriot-owned plantations led formerly neutral "grandees" to side with them.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Skirmishes at Williamson's Plantation, Cedar Springs, Rocky Mount, and Hanging Rock signaled widespread resistance to the new oaths throughout South Carolina.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In July 1780, Congress appointed Gates commander in the south; he was defeated at the Battle of Camden on August 16, leaving Cornwallis free to enter North Carolina.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Despite battlefield success, the British could not control the countryside and Patriot attacks continued; before moving north, Cornwallis sent Loyalist militia under Major Patrick Ferguson to cover his left flank, leaving their forces too far apart to provide mutual support.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In early October, Ferguson was defeated at the Battle of Kings Mountain, dispersing organized Loyalist resistance in the region.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Despite this, Cornwallis continued into North Carolina hoping for Loyalist support, while Washington replaced Gates with General Nathanael Greene in December 1780.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Greene divided his army, leading his main force southeast pursued by Cornwallis; a detachment was sent southwest under Daniel Morgan, who defeated Tarleton's British Legion at Cowpens on January 17, 1781, nearly eliminating it as a fighting force.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Patriots now held the initiative in the south, with the exception of a raid on Richmond led by Benedict Arnold in January 1781.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Greene led Cornwallis on a series of countermarches around North Carolina; by early March, the British were exhausted and short of supplies and Greene felt strong enough to fight the Battle of Guilford Court House on March 15.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Although victorious, Cornwallis suffered heavy casualties and retreated to Wilmington, North Carolina, seeking supplies and reinforcements.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Patriots now controlled most of the Carolinas and Georgia outside the coastal areas; after a minor reversal at the Battle of Hobkirk's Hill, they captured Fort Balfour on April 13 and recaptured Fort Watson and Fort Motte on April 15.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On June 6, Brigadier General Andrew Pickens captured Augusta, leaving the British in Georgia confined to Charleston and Savannah.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The assumption Loyalists would do most of the fighting left the British short of troops and battlefield victories came at the cost of losses they could not replace.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Despite halting Greene's advance at the Battle of Eutaw Springs on September 8, Cornwallis withdrew to Charleston with little to show for his campaign.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] From the beginning of the war, Bernardo de Gálvez, the Governor of Spanish Louisiana, allowed the Americans to import supplies and munitions into New Orleans, then ship them to Pittsburgh.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This provided an alternative transportation route for the Continental Army, bypassing the British blockade of the Atlantic Coast.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In February 1778, an expedition of militia to destroy British military supplies in settlements along the Cuyahoga River was halted by adverse weather.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Later in the year, a second campaign was undertaken to seize the Illinois Country from the British.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Virginia militia, *Canadien* settlers, and Indian allies commanded by Colonel George Rogers Clark captured Kaskaskia on July 4 and then secured Vincennes, though Vincennes was recaptured by Quebec Governor Henry Hamilton.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Spanish-aligned fur trader Francis Vigo, an American sympathizer, alerted Clark to the threat posed to his control of the west by Hamilton's position and in early 1779, the Virginians counter-attacked in the siege of Fort Vincennes and took Hamilton prisoner.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Clark secured western British Quebec as the American Northwest Territory in the Treaty of Paris as the Revolutionary War came to an end.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] When Spain joined France's war against Britain in the Anglo-French War in 1779, their treaty specifically excluded Spanish military action in North America.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Later that year, however, Gálvez initiated offensive operations against British outposts.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] First, he cleared British garrisons in Baton Rouge, Louisiana, Fort Bute, and Natchez, Mississippi, and captured five forts.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In doing so, Gálvez opened navigation on the Mississippi River north to the American settlement in Pittsburgh.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On May 25, 1780, British Colonel Henry Bird invaded Kentucky as part of a wider operation to clear American resistance from Quebec to the Gulf Coast.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Their advance on New Orleans was repelled by Spanish Governor Gálvez's offensive on Mobile.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Simultaneous British attacks were repulsed on St.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Louis by the Spanish Lieutenant Governor de Leyba, and on the Virginia County courthouse in Cahokia, Illinois, by Lieutenant Colonel Clark.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The British initiative under Bird from Detroit was ended at the rumored approach of Clark.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The scale of violence in the Licking River Valley, was extreme "even for frontier standards." It led to English and German settlements, who joined Clark's militia when the British and their hired German soldiers withdrew to the Great Lakes.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Americans responded with a major offensive along the Mad River in August which met with some success in the Battle of Piqua but did not end Indian raids.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] French soldier Augustin de La Balme led a Canadian militia in an attempt to capture Detroit, but they dispersed when Miami natives led by Little Turtle attacked the encamped settlers on November 5.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The war in the west stalemated with the British garrison sitting in Detroit and the Virginians expanding westward settlements north of the Ohio River in the face of British-allied Indian resistance.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In 1781, Galvez and Pollock campaigned east along the Gulf Coast to secure West Florida, including British-held Mobile and Pensacola.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The Spanish operations impaired the British supply of armaments to British Indian allies, which effectively suspended a military alliance to attack settlers between the Mississippi River and the Appalachian Mountains.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In 1782, large scale retaliations between settlers and Native Americans in the region included the Gnadenhutten massacre and the Crawford expedition.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The 1782 Battle of Blue Licks was one of the last major engagements of the war.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] News of the treaty between Great Britain and the United States arrived late that year.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] By this time, about 7% of Kentucky settlers had been killed in battles against Native Americans, contrasted with 1% of the population killed in the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Lingering resentments led to continued fighting in the west after the war officially ended.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Clinton spent most of 1781 based in New York City; he failed to construct a coherent operational strategy, partly due to his difficult relationship with Admiral Marriot Arbuthnot.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In Charleston, Cornwallis independently developed an aggressive plan for a campaign in Virginia, which he hoped would isolate Greene's army in the Carolinas and cause the collapse of Patriot resistance in the South.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This strategy was approved by Lord Germain in London, but neither informed Clinton.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Washington and Rochambeau discussed their options: Washington wanted to attack the British in New York, and Rochambeau wanted to attack them in Virginia, where Cornwallis's forces were less established.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Washington eventually gave way, and Lafayette took a combined Franco-American force into Virginia.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Clinton misinterpreted his movements as preparations for an attack on New York and instructed Cornwallis to establish a fortified sea base, where the Royal Navy could evacuate British troops to help defend New York.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] When Lafayette entered Virginia, Cornwallis complied with Clinton's orders and withdrew to Yorktown, where he constructed strong defenses and awaited evacuation.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] An agreement by the Spanish Navy to defend the French West Indies allowed Admiral François Joseph Paul de Grasse to relocate to the Atlantic seaboard, a move Arbuthnot did not anticipate.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] This provided Lafayette naval support, while the failure of previous combined operations at Newport and Savannah meant their coordination was planned more carefully.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Despite repeated urging from his subordinates, Cornwallis made no attempt to engage Lafayette before he could establish siege lines.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Expecting to be withdrawn within a few days, he also abandoned the outer defenses, which were promptly occupied by the besiegers and hastened British defeat.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On August 31, a Royal Navy fleet under Thomas Graves left New York for Yorktown.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] After landing troops and munitions for the besiegers on August 30, de Grasse remained in Chesapeake Bay and intercepted him on September 5; although the Battle of the Chesapeake was indecisive in terms of losses, Graves was forced to retreat, leaving Cornwallis isolated.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] An attempted breakout over the York River at Gloucester Point failed due to bad weather.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Under heavy bombardment with dwindling supplies, on October 16 Cornwallis sent emissaries to General Washington to negotiate surrender; after twelve hours of negotiations, the terms of surrender were finalized the following day.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Responsibility for defeat was the subject of fierce public debate between Cornwallis, Clinton, and Germain.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Clinton ultimately took most of the blame and spent the rest of his life in relative obscurity.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Subsequent to Yorktown, American forces were assigned to supervise the armistice between Washington and Clinton made to facilitate British departure following the January 1782 law of Parliament forbidding any further British offensive action in North America.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] British-American negotiations in Paris led to signed preliminary agreements in November 1782, which acknowledged US independence.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The enacted Congressional war objective, a British withdrawal from North America and cession of these regions to the US, was completed in stages in East Coast cities.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] In the US South, Generals Greene and Wayne observed the British removing their troops from Charleston on December 14, 1782.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Loyalist provincial militias of whites and free Blacks and Loyalists with slaves were transported to Nova Scotia and the British West Indies.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Native American allies of the British and some freed Blacks were left to escape unaided through the American lines.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] On April 9, 1783, Washington issued orders that "all acts of hostility" were to cease immediately.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] That same day, by arrangement with Washington, Carleton issued a similar order to British troops.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] As directed by a Congressional resolution of May 26, 1783, all non-commissioned officers and enlisted were furloughed "to their homes" until the "definitive treaty of peace", when they would be automatically discharged.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The US armies were directly disbanded in the field as of Washington's General Orders on June 2, 1783.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] Once the Treaty of Paris was signed with Britain on September 3, 1783, Washington resigned as commander-in-chief of the Continental Army.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p02] The last British occupation of New York City ended on November 25, 1783, with the departure of Clinton's replacement, General Sir Guy Carleton.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] To win their insurrection, Washington and the Continental Army needed to outlast the British will to fight.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] To restore British America, the British had to defeat the Continental Army quickly and compel the Second Continental Congress to retract its claim to self-governance.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Mays of The Citadel identifies three separate types of warfare during the Revolutionary War.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The first was a colonial conflict in which objections to imperial trade regulation were as significant as taxation policy.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The second was a civil war between American Patriots, American Loyalists, and those who preferred to remain neutral.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Particularly in the south, many battles were fought between Patriots and Loyalists with no British involvement, leading to divisions that continued after independence was achieved.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The third element was a global war between France, Spain, the Dutch Republic, and Britain, with America serving as one of several different war theaters.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] After entering the Revolutionary War in 1778, France provided the Americans money, weapons, soldiers, and naval assistance, while French troops fought under US command in North America.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] While Spain did not formally join the war in America, they provided access to the Mississippi River and captured British possessions on the Gulf of Mexico that denied bases to the Royal Navy, retook Menorca and besieged Gibraltar in Europe.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Although the Dutch Republic was no longer a major power prior to 1774, they still dominated the European carrying trade, and Dutch merchants made large profits by shipping French-supplied munitions to the Patriots.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] This ended when Britain declared war in December 1780, and the conflict proved disastrous to the Dutch economy.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The Americans stood to benefit if the Continental Army remained intact and the armed conflict became a protracted war.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] British supply lines were long, replacement of troops difficult, and the war was expensive.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Colonial populations were largely prosperous and depended on local production for food and supplies rather than on imports from Britain.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The thirteen colonies were spread across most of North American Atlantic seaboard, stretching 1,000 miles.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Most colonial farms were remote from the seaports, and control of four or five major ports did not give Britain control over American inland areas.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Each state had established internal distribution systems.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Motivation was also a major asset: each colonial capital had its own newspapers and printers, and the Patriots enjoyed more popular support than the Loyalists.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Britain hoped that the Loyalists would do much of the fighting, but found that the Loyalists did not engage as significantly as they had hoped.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] When the Revolutionary War began, the Second Continental Congress lacked a professional army or navy.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] However, each of the colonies had a long-established system of local militia, which were combat-tested in support of British regulars in the French and Indian War.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The colonial state legislatures independently funded and controlled their local militias.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Militiamen were lightly armed, had little training, and usually did not have uniforms.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Their units served for only a few weeks or months at a time and lacked the training and discipline of more experienced soldiers.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Local county militias were reluctant to travel far from home and were unavailable for extended operations.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] To compensate for this, the Continental Congress established a regular force known as the Continental Army on June 14, 1775, which proved to be the origin of the modern United States Army, and appointed Washington as its commander-in-chief.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] However, it suffered significantly from the lack of an effective training program and from largely inexperienced officers.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] One of Washington's most successful general officer recruits was Steuben, a veteran of the Prussian general staff who wrote the Revolutionary War Drill Manual.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Both sides used partisan warfare, but the state militias effectively suppressed Loyalist activity when British regulars were not in the area.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Washington designed the overall military strategy in cooperation with Congress, established the principle of civilian supremacy in military affairs, personally recruited his senior officer corps, and kept the states focused on a common goal.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Washington initially employed the inexperienced officers and untrained troops in Fabian strategies rather than risk frontal assaults against Britain's professional forces.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Over the course of the war, Washington lost more battles than he won, but he never surrendered his troops and maintained a fighting force in the face of British field armies.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] By prevailing European standards, the armies in America were relatively small, limited by lack of supplies and logistics.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The British were constrained by the logistical difficulty of transporting troops across the Atlantic and their dependence on local supplies.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Washington never directly commanded more than 17,000 men, and the combined Franco-American army in the decisive American victory at Yorktown was only about 19,000.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] At the beginning of 1776, Patriot forces consisted of 20,000 men, with two-thirds in the Continental Army and the other third in the state militias.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] About 250,000 American men served as regulars or as militia for the revolutionary cause during the war, but there were never more than 90,000 men under arms at any time.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] On the whole, American officers never equaled their British opponents in tactics and maneuvers, and they lost most of the pitched battles.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The great successes at Boston (1776), Saratoga (1777), and Yorktown (1781) were won by trapping the British far from base with a greater number of troops.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] After 1778, Washington's army was transformed into a more disciplined and effective force, mostly as a product of Baron von Steuben's military training.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] After the Battle of Monmouth, Washington came to realize that saving entire towns was not necessary, but preserving his army and keeping the revolutionary spirit alive was more important.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Although the Continental Congress was responsible for the war effort and provided supplies to the troops, Washington took it upon himself to pressure Congress and the state legislatures to provide the essentials of war; there was never nearly enough.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Congress evolved in its committee oversight and established the Board of War, which included members of the military.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Because the Board of War was also a committee ensnared with its own internal procedures, Congress also created the post of Secretary of War, appointing Major General Benjamin Lincoln to the position in February 1781.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Washington worked closely with Lincoln to coordinate civilian and military authorities and took charge of training and supplying the army.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] During the first summer of the war, Washington began outfitting schooners and other small seagoing vessels to prey on ships supplying the British in Boston.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The Second Continental Congress established the Continental Navy on October 13, 1775, and appointed Esek Hopkins as its first commander; for most of the war, the Continental Navy included only a handful of small frigates and sloops, supported by privateers.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] On November 10, 1775, Congress authorized the creation of the Continental Marines, which ultimately evolved into the United States Marine Corps.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] John Paul Jones became the first American naval hero when he captured HMS *Drake* on April 24, 1778, the first victory for any American military vessel in British waters.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The last such victory was by the frigate USS *Alliance*, commanded by Captain John Barry.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] On March 10, 1783, the *Alliance* outgunned HMS *Sybil* in a 45-minute duel while escorting Spanish gold from Havana to the Congress in Philadelphia.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] After Yorktown, all US Navy ships were sold or given away; it was the first time in America's history that it had no fighting forces on the high seas.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Congress primarily commissioned privateers to reduce costs and to take advantage of the large proportion of colonial sailors found in the British Empire.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] In total, they included 1,700 ships that successfully captured 2,283 enemy ships to damage the British effort and to enrich themselves with the proceeds from the sale of cargo and the ship itself.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] About 55,000 sailors served aboard American privateers during the war.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] At the beginning of the war, the Americans had no major international allies, since most nation-states waited to see how the conflict unfolded.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Over time, the Continental Army established its military credibility.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The decisive American victory at Saratoga convinced France, which was already a long-time rival of Britain, to offer the Americans the Treaty of Amity and Commerce.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The two nations also agreed to a defensive Treaty of Alliance to protect their trade and also guaranteed American independence from Britain.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] To engage the United States as a French ally militarily, the treaty was conditioned on Britain initiating a war on France to stop it from trading with the US.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Spain and the Dutch Republic were invited to join by both France and the United States in the treaty, but neither was responsive to the request.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] On June 13, 1778, France declared war on Great Britain, and it invoked the French military alliance with the US, which ensured additional US private support for French possessions in the Caribbean.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Washington worked closely with the soldiers and navy that France would send to America, primarily through Lafayette on his staff.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] French assistance made critical contributions required to defeat Cornwallis at Yorktown in 1781.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] The British military had considerable experience fighting in North America.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] However, in previous conflicts they benefited from local logistics and support from the colonial militia.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] In the American Revolutionary War, reinforcements had to come from Europe, and maintaining large armies over such distances was extremely complex; ships could take three months to cross the Atlantic, and orders from London were often outdated by the time they arrived.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] Prior to the conflict, the colonies were largely autonomous economic and political entities, with no centralized area of ultimate strategic importance.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] This meant that, unlike Europe where the fall of a capital city often ended wars, that in America continued even after the loss of major settlements such as Philadelphia, the seat of Congress, New York, and Charleston.
[src:baltimore-clipper/american-revolutionary-war-p03] British power was reliant on the Royal Navy, whose dominance allowed them to resupply their own expeditionary forces while preventing access to enemy ports.
